  export const questions = {
    intro: [
      { year: "2023", q: "Which economist defined economics as 'the science which studies human behaviour as a relationship between ends and scarce means which have alternative uses'?", options: ["A. Adam Smith", "B. Alfred Marshall", "C. Lionel Robbins", "D. John Maynard Keynes"], answer: "C", exp: "Lionel Robbins gave this famous scarcity-based definition in his 1932 essay. It is the most widely accepted modern definition of economics." },
      { year: "2023", q: "Which of the following is a POSITIVE economic statement?", options: ["A. The government should reduce poverty", "B. Income should be equally distributed", "C. A rise in price leads to a fall in quantity demanded", "D. Nigeria should produce more food"], answer: "C", exp: "Positive statements are factual and testable (what IS). Options A, B, and D are normative — they express value judgements about what SHOULD be." },
      { year: "2022", q: "The basic economic problem arises because:", options: ["A. Governments fail to plan properly", "B. Human wants are unlimited while resources are scarce", "C. Technology is insufficient", "D. People are greedy"], answer: "B", exp: "Scarcity — the gap between unlimited wants and limited resources — is the fundamental economic problem that forces all economies to make choices." },
      { year: "2021", q: "Which of the following is a MACROECONOMIC variable?", options: ["A. The price of garri in Kano market", "B. The output of a Dangote cement factory", "C. The national unemployment rate", "D. The wage of a teacher in Lagos"], answer: "C", exp: "National unemployment rate is an aggregate variable covering the entire economy. The other options are microeconomic (individual prices, outputs, wages)." },
      { year: "2019", q: "Economics is often described as a science because it:", options: ["A. Employs the use of laboratory experiments", "B. Engages accurate prediction of human beings", "C. Makes use of controlled experiments", "D. Uses scientific methods to explain observed phenomena"], answer: "D", exp: "Economics is a social science because it applies scientific methods — observation, hypothesis, testing — to explain economic phenomena, even though it cannot conduct controlled laboratory experiments like natural sciences." },
    { year: "2019", q: "When a generalization is made based on observed facts, it is:", options: ["A. Normative reasoning", "B. Theoretical reasoning", "C. Inductive reasoning", "D. Deductive reasoning"], answer: "C", exp: "Inductive reasoning moves from specific observations to general conclusions. Deductive reasoning moves from general principles to specific predictions. Observing facts and generalising from them is inductive." },
    { year: "2019", q: "Endogenous variable is:", options: ["A. A variable that is determined inside the model", "B. A variable that is determined outside the model", "C. A variable that is not in the model", "D. A variable that is not part of the theory"], answer: "A", exp: "Endogenous variables are determined within the economic model itself (e.g. price and quantity in a demand-supply model). Exogenous variables are determined outside the model (e.g. government policy, weather)." },
    { year: "2019", q: "Macroeconomics focuses on the following units in an aggregative manner:", options: ["A. Individual consumers, individual firms, government and external sector", "B. Government, household firms, individual consumers and external sector", "C. Household, firms, government and external sector", "D. Individual consumer, household firms and manufacturing sector"], answer: "C", exp: "Macroeconomics studies the economy in aggregate — it focuses on households, firms, government, and the external sector as groups, not as individual units. Microeconomics studies individual consumers and firms." },
    { year: "2019", q: "Which of the following is a positive economic statement?", options: ["A. The government should reduce unemployment", "B. Nigeria ought to diversify its economy", "C. An increase in money supply leads to inflation", "D. Income should be distributed equally"], answer: "C", exp: "Positive statements are factual and testable — they describe what IS. 'An increase in money supply leads to inflation' is testable using data. The others express value judgements (normative statements)." },
    { year: "2019", q: "Which of the following best describes the scope of microeconomics?", options: ["A. The study of aggregate national output", "B. The study of individual markets, firms and consumers", "C. The study of national inflation and unemployment", "D. The study of money supply and interest rates"], answer: "B", exp: "Microeconomics examines individual economic units — specific markets, individual consumers, and individual firms. It studies price determination, consumer behaviour, and firm production decisions at the individual level." },
    { year: "2015", q: "Which of the following is not concerned with macroeconomics?", options: ["A. Aggregate level of outputs", "B. General level of prices", "C. Growth of real output", "D. Price of a commodity"], answer: "D", exp: "Price of a specific commodity is a microeconomic variable. Macroeconomics deals with aggregate variables like total output, general price level, and overall growth." },
      { year: "2015", q: "Microeconomics is the study of:", options: ["A. The output of the entire economy", "B. The total number of workers employed in Nigeria", "C. The general level of prices in the Nigerian economy", "D. The output and price of wheat in Nigeria"], answer: "D", exp: "Microeconomics studies individual markets, specific goods, and individual economic units. The price and output of wheat in a specific market is a microeconomic topic." },
      { year: "2015", q: "The following are economic agents in any economy EXCEPT:", options: ["A. Government", "B. Household", "C. Firm", "D. Central Bank"], answer: "D", exp: "The three main economic agents are households, firms, and government. The Central Bank is a specific institution under government, not a separate economic agent in the basic circular flow model." },
      { year: "2015", q: "Which of the following is not referring to the word 'economic'?", options: ["A. Is scarce", "B. Is limited", "C. Commands a price", "D. Unlimited"], answer: "D", exp: "Economic goods are scarce, limited, and command a price. Unlimited availability describes free goods (like air), not economic goods." },],
    basic: [
      { year: "2023", q: "Opportunity cost is BEST defined as:", options: ["A. The total money spent on a good", "B. The value of the next best alternative forgone", "C. The profit lost by a firm", "D. The cost of producing one more unit"], answer: "B", exp: "Opportunity cost is not about money — it is the value of the best alternative you sacrificed when making a choice. It applies to all economic agents." },
      { year: "2023", q: "A point INSIDE the Production Possibility Curve (PPC) represents:", options: ["A. Full employment of resources", "B. An unattainable level of output", "C. Productive inefficiency", "D. Technological advancement"], answer: "C", exp: "Inside the PPC means resources are not fully utilised — some are idle or misallocated. This is productive inefficiency. Points on the curve represent efficiency." },
      { year: "2022", q: "The PPC shifts OUTWARD when there is:", options: ["A. A rise in consumer demand", "B. Technological advancement", "C. A fall in the price level", "D. Increased government spending"], answer: "B", exp: "The PPC shifts outward when the economy's productive capacity increases — through better technology, discovery of new resources, or improvement in education and skills." },
      { year: "2022", q: "In a mixed economy like Nigeria:", options: ["A. Only private firms produce goods", "B. The government controls all resources", "C. Both government and private sector allocate resources", "D. Resources are allocated by tradition and custom"], answer: "C", exp: "Nigeria is a mixed economy — the private sector operates freely in most markets while the government controls key sectors (e.g. NNPC, infrastructure) and provides public goods." },
      { year: "2019", q: "From a PPC graph, a point inside the curve shows:", options: ["A. Productive efficiency", "B. Allocative efficiency", "C. Product inefficiency", "D. Product efficiency"], answer: "C", exp: "A point inside (below) the PPC represents productive inefficiency — resources are not being fully or optimally used. The economy could produce more of both goods by moving to the curve." },
    { year: "2019", q: "Suppose public expenditure as a percentage of GDP is 40-50% in several countries. Which type of economy exists in these countries?", options: ["A. Mixed", "B. Planned", "C. Pure market", "D. Traditional"], answer: "A", exp: "When government spends 33-50% of GDP, the economy has significant public sector involvement alongside private sector activity — this is characteristic of a mixed economy. A pure market economy would have minimal government spending." },
    { year: "2019", q: "The decision to consume more of one product under normal circumstances will imply:", options: ["A. More of another product will be consumed", "B. Less of the product will be consumed", "C. No other products will be consumed", "D. Less of another product will be consumed"], answer: "D", exp: "This reflects the concept of opportunity cost and scarcity — with a limited budget, consuming more of one good means consuming less of another. This is the basis of the downward-sloping budget line." },
    { year: "2019", q: "Which of the following best illustrates the concept of opportunity cost?", options: ["A. A student spends ₦5,000 on a textbook", "B. A student chooses to study instead of watching a football match", "C. A government increases its budget", "D. A firm increases its output"], answer: "B", exp: "Opportunity cost is the value of the next best alternative forgone. By choosing to study, the student forgoes the enjoyment of watching the football match — that enjoyment is the opportunity cost of studying." },
    { year: "2019", q: "Classical models of economic growth based their analysis on the assumption that:", options: ["A. There is full employment of resources", "B. There is partial utilization of capital", "C. Prices and wages are rigid downward", "D. The saving ratio is low"], answer: "A", exp: "Classical economists assumed that markets always clear and the economy operates at full employment in the long run. This contrasts with Keynesian theory, which showed that economies can be stuck below full employment." },
    { year: "2021", q: "The reward for LAND as a factor of production is:", options: ["A. Wages", "B. Interest", "C. Profit", "D. Rent"], answer: "D", exp: "The four factors and their rewards: Land = Rent, Labour = Wages, Capital = Interest, Enterprise = Profit." },
      { year: "2015", q: "The fundamental problem of economics is:", options: ["A. Establishment of a political framework for production", "B. To establish equitable distribution of income", "C. The scarcity of productive resources relative to society's unlimited wants", "D. Finding determinants between forces of supply and demand"], answer: "C", exp: "The fundamental economic problem is scarcity — productive resources are limited while human wants are unlimited. This forces all societies to make choices about allocation." },
      { year: "2015", q: "Economic problem occurs when:", options: ["A. There is scarcity relative to demand", "B. There are no buyers for goods", "C. Many people are out of work", "D. All raw materials are imported"], answer: "A", exp: "Economic problems arise from scarcity — when available resources are insufficient relative to demand. This forces choices and trade-offs." },
      { year: "2015", q: "Economic goods are termed scarce goods when they are:", options: ["A. Not available in sufficient quantities to satisfy effective demand", "B. Not produced in sufficient quantities to satisfy effective demand", "C. Of high quality", "D. Of primary importance in satisfying the needs of a society"], answer: "B", exp: "Goods are scarce when production is insufficient to satisfy effective demand at zero price — forcing a price to be charged to ration limited supply." },
      { year: "2015", q: "Which of the following is an example of a free good?", options: ["A. Dinner you did not pay for", "B. Your rented apartment", "C. Free education", "D. Water in the ocean"], answer: "D", exp: "A free good has no opportunity cost and is available in unlimited supply. Water in the ocean is not scarce — no one has to give up anything to obtain it. Free education and unpaid dinners still have resource costs." },
      { year: "2015", q: "A major factor contributing to productivity is:", options: ["A. The labour force", "B. The rate of GDP per year", "C. The baby boom generation", "D. Immigration of young workers"], answer: "A", exp: "The labour force — its size, skills, education, and health — is the most direct factor contributing to productivity. Human capital improvements drive output per worker." },
      { year: "2015", q: "The development of an economic hypothesis through intuition, insight, or logic is associated with:", options: ["A. Induction", "B. Deduction", "C. Policy economics", "D. Normative economics"], answer: "B", exp: "Deduction starts from general principles or theory and derives specific conclusions through logic. Induction works in the opposite direction — from specific observations to general conclusions." },
    ],
    tool: [
        { year: "2020", q: "In economics, the mathematical expression between two or more variables is known as:", options: ["A. Equality", "B. Identity", "C. Equation", "D. Variables"], answer: "C", exp: "An equation expresses a mathematical relationship between two or more variables. In economics, equations like Qd = 100 - 5P express how variables are related. An identity is always true (like MPC + MPS = 1), while an equation holds only under specific conditions." },
        { year: "2020", q: "The statement 'All Chinese are racists, Dr. Yeung is Chinese, therefore he is a racist' is an example of:", options: ["A. Inductive reasoning", "B. Deductive reasoning", "C. Positive statement", "D. Normative statement"], answer: "B", exp: "Deductive reasoning applies a general principle to a specific case to reach a conclusion. Starting from a general premise ('all Chinese are racists') and applying it to a specific case (Dr. Yeung) is deductive — even though the premise is false and discriminatory." },
        { year: "2020", q: "Implicit costs differ from explicit costs in that implicit costs:", options: ["A. Are payments made to outsiders for resources", "B. Are the opportunity costs of using owner-supplied resources", "C. Are recorded in the firm's accounting books", "D. Are always greater than explicit costs"], answer: "B", exp: "Implicit costs are the opportunity costs of resources owned by the firm and used in production — such as the owner's time and capital. They are not actual cash payments but represent foregone income. Explicit costs are actual monetary payments to outside suppliers." },
        { year: "2020", q: "Which of the following best describes the difference between average cost and marginal cost?", options: ["A. Average cost is total cost divided by output; marginal cost is the cost of the last unit", "B. Average cost is always greater than marginal cost", "C. Marginal cost is total cost divided by output", "D. Average cost equals marginal cost at all levels of output"], answer: "A", exp: "Average Total Cost (ATC) = TC/Q — cost per unit of output. Marginal Cost (MC) = ΔTC/ΔQ — the additional cost of producing one more unit. The MC curve intersects the ATC curve at ATC's minimum point." },
         { year: "2019", q: "If the demand function for a product is Qs = 30 - 4P, and price is 4 and quantity is 14, what is the price elasticity of demand?", options: ["A. 1.14", "B. 1.7", "C. 14.1", "D. 7.1"], answer: "A", exp: "PED = (dQ/dP) × (P/Q). The slope dQ/dP = -4. PED = |-4| × (4/14) = 4 × 0.2857 = 1.14. Since PED > 1, demand is elastic at this price-quantity combination." },
    { year: "2019", q: "In economic analysis, functional relationships can be expressed as:", options: ["A. Algebraic equations and geometric graphs only", "B. Statistical tables only", "C. Written descriptions only", "D. Any combination of algebraic, geometric and statistical forms"], answer: "D", exp: "Economic relationships can be expressed in multiple ways — algebraic equations (Qd = 100 - 5P), geometric graphs (demand curve), or statistical/tabular form. Each method has advantages for different purposes." },
    ],
    price: [
      { year: "2023", q: "A rise in the price of Pepsi leads to an increase in demand for Coca-Cola. This is because they are:", options: ["A. Complementary goods", "B. Substitute goods", "C. Inferior goods", "D. Public goods"], answer: "B", exp: "Substitute goods compete with each other. When the price of one rises, consumers switch to the cheaper alternative, increasing demand for the substitute." },
      { year: "2023", q: "If PED = 0.3, demand is:", options: ["A. Elastic", "B. Unit elastic", "C. Inelastic", "D. Perfectly elastic"], answer: "C", exp: "PED less than 1 means inelastic demand — quantity demanded is not very responsive to price change. Common for necessities like salt, fuel, and medicine." },
      { year: "2022", q: "A price CEILING set below equilibrium will cause:", options: ["A. A surplus of the good", "B. A shortage of the good", "C. No change in quantity demanded", "D. An increase in supply"], answer: "B", exp: "Price ceiling (maximum price) set below equilibrium keeps price too low — quantity demanded exceeds quantity supplied — causing a shortage. Example: rent control." },
      { year: "2022", q: "Which of the following will shift the demand curve for beef to the RIGHT?", options: ["A. A fall in the price of beef", "B. A rise in consumer income (beef is a normal good)", "C. A fall in population", "D. A rise in the price of a complementary good"], answer: "B", exp: "Rising income increases demand for normal goods — shifting the curve right. A price change causes movement ALONG the curve, not a shift of it." },
      { year: "2021", q: "The demand for tractors by Nigerian farmers is an example of:", options: ["A. Joint demand", "B. Composite demand", "C. Derived demand", "D. Effective demand"], answer: "C", exp: "Demand for tractors is derived from demand for agricultural products. Factors of production are demanded because of demand for the final good they help produce." },
      { year: "2020", q: "A perfectly inelastic supply curve is:", options: ["A. A straight vertical line", "B. A straight horizontal line", "C. An upward sloping line", "D. A downward sloping line"], answer: "A", exp: "Perfectly inelastic supply (PES = 0) means quantity supplied does not change regardless of price — the supply curve is a vertical line. Examples: supply of land, rare works of art, seats in a stadium." },
      { year: "2020", q: "Which of the following is most likely to have an inverse relationship?", options: ["A. Price and quantity supplied", "B. Income and quantity consumed for normal goods", "C. Taxes and quantity bought", "D. Tastes and quantity demanded"], answer: "C", exp: "Taxes raise the price of goods, which reduces quantity bought — an inverse relationship. Price and quantity supplied have a direct relationship (law of supply). Income and normal goods consumption have a direct relationship." },
      { year: "2020", q: "When an increase in the price of steel causes an increase in the production of cars, the supply of cars is:", options: ["A. Complementary", "B. Composite", "C. Competitive", "D. Derived"], answer: "D", exp: "This is derived supply — the supply of one good (cars) arises from or is linked to demand for another good. When steel prices rise, steel producers supply more steel, enabling more car production. This concept is similar to derived demand." },
      { year: "2020", q: "A good whose consumer purchases more as its price declines can be described as:", options: ["A. Inferior good", "B. Giffen good", "C. Ostentatious good", "D. Normal good"], answer: "D", exp: "For a normal good, quantity demanded increases as price falls (law of demand). An inferior good's demand rises as price falls AND as income falls. A Giffen good is an extreme inferior good where demand RISES as price rises — opposite of normal goods." },
      { year: "2020", q: "In calculating cross price elasticity of demand, which statement is true?", options: ["A. It involves only one commodity", "B. It involves two commodities while regular PED involves one", "C. It requires income of the consumer while regular PED does not", "D. Regular PED requires income while cross elasticity does not"], answer: "B", exp: "Cross Price Elasticity of Demand (XED) measures how the demand for one good responds to a price change in ANOTHER good — so it involves two commodities. Regular Price Elasticity of Demand (PED) involves only one commodity — its own price and quantity." },
      { year: "2020", q: "Bread and water are said to be jointly demanded. If the price of bread increases, the quantity demanded for water will:", options: ["A. Rise", "B. Fall", "C. Price of water rises", "D. Price of water falls"], answer: "B", exp: "Joint (complementary) demand means goods are consumed together. When price of bread rises, demand for bread falls — and since water is demanded jointly with bread, demand for water also falls. This is negative cross elasticity (XED < 0)." },
      { year: "2020", q: "Average Fixed Cost (AFC) behaves in which of the following ways as output increases?", options: ["A. It rises continuously", "B. It falls continuously", "C. It remains constant", "D. It first falls then rises"], answer: "B", exp: "AFC = Fixed Cost / Output. Since fixed costs are constant, as output (denominator) increases, AFC falls continuously. This spreading of fixed costs over more units is called 'spreading overhead' — it pulls ATC down at low output levels." },
       { year: "2019", q: "When a kilogram of carrot is ₦8.00, 20 kilograms are demanded. When price falls to ₦6.00, 30 kilograms are demanded. The elasticity of demand equals:", options: ["A. 11", "B. 12", "C. 2", "D. 0.5"], answer: "C", exp: "PED = (% change in Qd) / (% change in P) = [(30-20)/20 × 100] / [(8-6)/8 × 100] = (50%) / (25%) = 2. Since PED = 2 > 1, demand is elastic." },
    { year: "2019", q: "The quantity of a commodity a consumer is willing and able to buy at a particular time is called:", options: ["A. Demand", "B. Supply", "C. Desire", "D. Wish"], answer: "A", exp: "Demand is defined as willingness AND ability to purchase at a given price. Mere desire or wish without purchasing power does not constitute demand in economics. Effective demand requires both willingness and ability to pay." },
    { year: "2019", q: "Which of the following shows why the individual demand curve for a good usually slopes downward from left to right?", options: ["A. More commodities are offered for sale at lower than higher prices", "B. Prices are usually falling when demand is low", "C. Marginal utility falls as consumption increases", "D. The higher the price the higher the quantity offered for sale"], answer: "C", exp: "The demand curve slopes downward because of diminishing marginal utility — as more units are consumed, each additional unit gives less satisfaction, so consumers are only willing to pay a lower price for additional units." },
    { year: "2019", q: "Deliberate attempt to limit imports is called:", options: ["A. Trade protection", "B. Trade management", "C. Export substitution", "D. Import substitution"], answer: "A", exp: "Trade protection refers to deliberate government policies designed to limit imports and protect domestic industries. Methods include tariffs, quotas, and embargoes. Import substitution is a specific strategy of producing domestically what was previously imported." },
    { year: "2019", q: "Which exchange rate regime is purely determined by the forces of demand and supply?", options: ["A. Fixed exchange rate", "B. Flexible exchange rate", "C. Modified exchange rate", "D. Principal exchange rate"], answer: "B", exp: "A flexible (floating) exchange rate is determined entirely by market forces — demand and supply of currencies. Fixed exchange rates are set by government. Managed float involves occasional central bank intervention." },
    { year: "2019", q: "Which would NOT be a reason for a government to impose a quota on imports?", options: ["A. To support strategic industry", "B. To raise tax revenue", "C. To prevent dumping", "D. To retaliate against other countries"], answer: "B", exp: "A quota limits the quantity of imports — it does NOT raise tax revenue (that is what tariffs do). Quotas are used to protect strategic industries, prevent dumping, and retaliate against trading partners." },
    { year: "2019", q: "One factor that is NOT underlying fluctuations in exchange rates is:", options: ["A. Bank influence", "B. Capital movements", "C. Changes in price", "D. Savings"], answer: "D", exp: "Exchange rates are influenced by capital movements, inflation differentials, interest rates, speculation, and central bank intervention. Domestic savings rates do not directly cause exchange rate fluctuations." },
    { year: "2019", q: "The relationship between elasticity of demand and total revenue shows that when demand is elastic:", options: ["A. A price rise increases total revenue", "B. A price fall decreases total revenue", "C. A price fall increases total revenue", "D. Price changes do not affect total revenue"], answer: "C", exp: "When demand is elastic (PED > 1), a price fall causes a proportionately larger rise in quantity demanded — so total revenue (P × Q) increases. This is why firms with elastic demand products should cut prices to boost revenue." },
    { year: "2015", q: "The demand for a good is price inelastic if:", options: ["A. The price elasticity is one", "B. The price elasticity is less than one", "C. The price elasticity is greater than one", "D. The price elasticity is negative"], answer: "B", exp: "Price inelastic demand means PED < 1 — quantity demanded is not very responsive to price changes. Common for necessities like salt, petrol, and medicine." },
      { year: "2015", q: "The type of price elasticity where quantity demanded remains unchanged despite changes in price is:", options: ["A. Inelastic", "B. Perfectly inelastic", "C. Infinitely elastic", "D. Perfectly elastic"], answer: "B", exp: "Perfectly inelastic demand (PED = 0) means quantity demanded does not change at all regardless of price changes. The demand curve is a vertical line." },
      { year: "2015", q: "The income elasticity of demand is defined as the responsiveness of:", options: ["A. Quantity demanded to a change in price", "B. Price to a change in income", "C. Quantity demanded to a change in income", "D. Price to a change in quantity"], answer: "C", exp: "YED = % change in quantity demanded ÷ % change in income. It measures how sensitive demand is to changes in consumer income." },
      { year: "2015", q: "If commodities X and Y are substitutes, their cross elasticity of demand will be:", options: ["A. Positive", "B. Zero", "C. One", "D. Negative"], answer: "A", exp: "Substitutes have positive cross elasticity — when the price of X rises, demand for Y increases. Complements have negative XED (e.g. car and fuel)." },
      { year: "2015", q: "The law of supply states that, other things being constant, as price increases:", options: ["A. Supply increases", "B. Supply decreases", "C. Quantity supplied increases", "D. Quantity supplied decreases"], answer: "C", exp: "An important distinction: price changes cause movement ALONG the supply curve (change in quantity supplied), not a shift of the entire supply curve (change in supply)." },
      { year: "2015", q: "A tariff is a tax imposed on:", options: ["A. Imported goods", "B. Exported goods", "C. Domestic goods", "D. Consumer goods"], answer: "A", exp: "A tariff is specifically a tax on imported goods. It raises the price of imports, making domestic alternatives relatively cheaper and protecting local industries." },
      { year: "2015", q: "When the government introduces an indirect tax on a good, which of the following best describes the effect?", options: ["A. Producers bear the full burden of the tax", "B. Consumers bear the full burden of the tax", "C. The tax burden is shared between consumers and producers", "D. The price falls and quantity rises"], answer: "C", exp: "An indirect tax shifts the supply curve left, raising price and reducing quantity. The burden is shared — consumers pay a higher price and producers receive a lower price net of tax. The exact split depends on elasticity." }, ],
    consumer: [
      { year: "2023", q: "When Total Utility is at its maximum, Marginal Utility is:", options: ["A. Rising", "B. Equal to average utility", "C. Negative", "D. Zero"], answer: "D", exp: "Total utility is maximised at the point where consuming one more unit adds nothing — MU = 0. Beyond this, MU becomes negative and TU falls." },
      { year: "2022", q: "An indifference curve is CONVEX to the origin because of:", options: ["A. The law of demand", "B. Diminishing marginal rate of substitution", "C. Increasing returns to scale", "D. The income effect"], answer: "B", exp: "As more of good X is consumed, the consumer gives up less and less of good Y for each additional unit of X — diminishing MRS causes the convex shape." },
      { year: "2022", q: "Consumer equilibrium using indifference curve analysis is achieved where:", options: ["A. The budget line cuts the indifference curve", "B. Total utility is at its minimum", "C. The highest attainable indifference curve is tangent to the budget line", "D. MU = price of the good"], answer: "C", exp: "The tangency point gives the highest satisfaction attainable given the consumer's budget. At this point, MRS = price ratio (Px/Py)." },
      { year: "2021", q: "The equi-marginal principle states that consumer equilibrium is achieved when:", options: ["A. MU of all goods is zero", "B. MU/P is equal for all goods consumed", "C. Total expenditure equals income", "D. The budget line shifts outward"], answer: "B", exp: "Consumer maximises utility when the MU per Naira spent is equal for all goods: MUx/Px = MUy/Py. This is the equi-marginal or equal-marginal principle." },
      { year: "2019", q: "Given the law of diminishing marginal utility, if consuming 2 oranges gives Total Utility of 16 and consuming 3 gives TU of 24, what is the Marginal Utility of the 3rd orange?", options: ["A. 0", "B. 0.5", "C. 7", "D. 8"], answer: "D", exp: "MU = Change in TU / Change in quantity = (24 - 16) / (3 - 2) = 8/1 = 8. From the table, X = MU of 2nd orange = 16 - 9 = 7. Wait — re-reading: TU at 2 = 16, TU at 1 = 9, so MU at 2 = 16-9 = 7. X = 7." },
      { year: "2019", q: "An indifference curve explains:", options: ["A. All combinations of two goods that give the same total utility", "B. The maximum amount a consumer can spend on two goods", "C. The relationship between price and quantity demanded", "D. How a consumer maximises profit"], answer: "A", exp: "An indifference curve shows all combinations of two goods that provide the consumer with exactly the same level of total satisfaction (utility). The consumer is indifferent between any two points on the same curve." },
      { year: "2019", q: "The Marginal Rate of Substitution (MRS) on an indifference curve represents:", options: ["A. The rate at which a consumer substitutes one good for another while maintaining the same utility", "B. The slope of the budget line", "C. The ratio of prices of two goods", "D. The change in total utility from consuming more of a good"], answer: "A", exp: "MRS is the rate at which a consumer is willing to give up one good to get one more unit of another good, while staying on the same indifference curve (same utility level). At consumer equilibrium, MRS = price ratio." },
      { year: "2019", q: "Shifts in the consumption curve are caused by all of the following EXCEPT changes in:", options: ["A. Asset holdings", "B. Income level", "C. Price level expectations", "D. Credit availability"], answer: "B", exp: "Income level causes movement ALONG the consumption function (C = a + bY), not a shift of it. Changes in assets, price expectations, and credit availability shift the entire consumption function up or down." },
      { year: "2019", q: "The basic properties of an indifference curve include all EXCEPT:", options: ["A. They slope downward from left to right", "B. They are convex to the origin", "C. Higher curves represent lower satisfaction", "D. Two indifference curves cannot intersect"], answer: "C", exp: "Higher indifference curves represent MORE satisfaction (more of both goods), not less. The four key properties are: downward sloping, convex to origin, higher = more satisfaction, and they never cross." },
       { year: "2015", q: "An increase in money income with constant prices results in:", options: ["A. Inward parallel shift in the budget line", "B. Outward parallel shift in the budget line", "C. Budget line remains constant", "D. Rotation of the budget line"], answer: "B", exp: "Higher income means the consumer can afford more of both goods — the budget line shifts outward (rightward) in a parallel manner since prices have not changed." },
     ],
    firm: [
      { year: "2023", q: "The law of diminishing returns states that as more variable input is added to a fixed factor:", options: ["A. Total product falls immediately", "B. Marginal product eventually falls", "C. Fixed costs increase", "D. Average cost falls continuously"], answer: "B", exp: "Eventually adding more labour to fixed capital causes overcrowding — each extra worker adds less to output than the previous one. MP eventually falls." },
      { year: "2022", q: "When Marginal Product (MP) exceeds Average Product (AP):", options: ["A. AP is at its maximum", "B. AP is falling", "C. AP is rising", "D. TP is falling"], answer: "C", exp: "When MP > AP, each new worker is above average — pulling the average up. AP rises. AP only falls when MP < AP. MP = AP at AP's maximum." },
      { year: "2022", q: "Which of the following is a FIXED cost?", options: ["A. Cost of raw materials", "B. Workers' overtime pay", "C. Factory rent", "D. Electricity used in production"], answer: "C", exp: "Fixed costs don't change with output — factory rent is paid whether or not production occurs. Raw materials, overtime, and electricity are variable costs." },
      { year: "2021", q: "Profit maximisation occurs where:", options: ["A. TR is greatest", "B. TC is lowest", "C. MC = MR", "D. AC = AR"], answer: "C", exp: "Firms maximise profit at the output level where MC = MR. If MC < MR, increasing output adds more to revenue than cost. If MC > MR, output should be reduced." },
      { year: "2020", q: "A firm declares normal profit of ₦400. If the owner invests ₦5,000 and interest rate on bonds is 10%, the firm:", options: ["A. Should continue to produce and invest in bonds", "B. Should discontinue production and invest in bonds", "C. Is making economic profit", "D. Is a sole trader who invests in bonds"], answer: "B", exp: "Opportunity cost of capital = 10% × ₦5,000 = ₦500. Normal profit (₦400) < Opportunity cost (₦500). The owner would earn more (₦500) by investing in bonds than staying in production (₦400). Therefore, the firm should discontinue and invest in bonds." },
      { year: "2020", q: "At the profit-maximising level of output, which of the following is true?", options: ["A. Δπ/ΔQ = 0", "B. Δπ/ΔQ > 0", "C. Δπ/ΔQ < 0", "D. Δπ/ΔQ = 1"], answer: "A", exp: "At the profit-maximising output, marginal profit (Δπ/ΔQ) equals zero — producing one more unit adds nothing to profit. This is equivalent to the MC = MR condition. If Δπ/ΔQ > 0, increase output. If < 0, reduce output." },
      { year: "2020", q: "A perfectly competitive firm is preferred to a monopolist because the perfect competitor:", options: ["A. Produces more output", "B. Charges less price", "C. Makes less profits", "D. Improves welfare more"], answer: "D", exp: "Perfect competition is preferred on welfare grounds — it achieves both productive efficiency (P = min ATC) and allocative efficiency (P = MC). More output at lower price improves consumer welfare compared to monopoly which restricts output and raises price." },
      { year: "2020", q: "Explicit costs differ from implicit costs in that explicit costs:", options: ["A. Include the opportunity cost of owner's resources", "B. Are actual monetary payments made to external suppliers", "C. Are never recorded in accounting books", "D. Are always smaller than implicit costs"], answer: "B", exp: "Explicit costs are actual cash payments to outside parties — wages paid to workers, rent paid to landlords, raw materials purchased. Implicit costs are the opportunity costs of owner-supplied resources (owner's time, owner's capital invested in the business)." },
      { year: "2020", q: "Which of the following best explains the four features of a perfectly competitive firm?", options: ["A. Many sellers, differentiated products, barriers to entry, price maker", "B. Few sellers, homogeneous products, free entry, price taker", "C. Many sellers, homogeneous products, free entry and exit, price taker", "D. Many sellers, unique products, no barriers, price maker"], answer: "C", exp: "Perfect competition requires: (1) Many buyers and sellers, (2) Homogeneous (identical) products, (3) Free entry and exit of firms, (4) Perfect information, (5) Each firm is a price taker. Differentiated products and price-making power characterise imperfect competition." },
       { year: "2020", q: "Economies of scale lead to:", options: ["A. Rising short-run marginal cost", "B. Falling long-run average cost", "C. Increasing fixed costs", "D. Falling marginal product"], answer: "B", exp: "Economies of scale occur when increasing output reduces long-run average cost — making large-scale production more efficient than small-scale production." },
      { year: "2015", q: "An industry is:", options: ["A. A group of firms producing differentiated products", "B. A group of firms producing distinct commodities", "C. A group of firms producing related goods", "D. A group of firms producing unrelated goods"], answer: "C", exp: "An industry consists of all firms producing related or similar goods that serve as substitutes for each other. For example, the cement industry includes all firms producing cement." },
      { year: "2019", q: "40 men were employed in a farm and produced an average of 30 tonnes of cassava per person. The total product is:", options: ["A. 1,100 tonnes", "B. 1,300 tonnes", "C. 1,400 tonnes", "D. 1,200 tonnes"], answer: "D", exp: "Total Product = Average Product × Number of Workers = 30 tonnes × 40 workers = 1,200 tonnes. This directly applies the formula TP = AP × L." },
    { year: "2019", q: "If the supply curve of the labour market is S = 4L + 8, what is L when S = 20?", options: ["A. 3", "B. 2", "C. 4", "D. 5"], answer: "A", exp: "Substituting S = 20: 20 = 4L + 8. Therefore 4L = 20 - 8 = 12. L = 12/4 = 3. This is a simple algebraic manipulation of the supply function." },
    { year: "2019", q: "Which of the following will cause an increase in cost of production?", options: ["A. Hyper-inflation", "B. Demand-pull inflation", "C. Cost-push inflation", "D. Structural inflation"], answer: "C", exp: "Cost-push inflation is directly caused by rising production costs (wages, raw materials, energy). The higher costs push up prices. Demand-pull inflation comes from excess demand, not from increased production costs." },
    { year: "2019", q: "All of the following describe conditions necessary for a perfect market EXCEPT:", options: ["A. Lack of homogeneity of goods", "B. Large number of buyers and sellers", "C. Perfect knowledge", "D. Portability of goods"], answer: "A", exp: "Perfect competition requires HOMOGENEOUS (identical) products — lack of homogeneity (product differentiation) is a feature of imperfect markets like monopolistic competition. The other options are conditions for a perfect market." },
    { year: "2019", q: "Economists refer to private goods as:", options: ["A. Non-rival and non-excludable", "B. Rivalrous and excludable", "C. Non-rival and excludable", "D. Rivalrous and non-excludable"], answer: "B", exp: "Private goods are rivalrous (one person's consumption reduces availability to others) and excludable (people can be prevented from consuming them by charging a price). Public goods are the opposite: non-rival and non-excludable." },
    { year: "2015", q: "The short run can be defined as the period of time during which:", options: ["A. At least one of the firm's inputs is fixed", "B. All inputs are variable", "C. All inputs are fixed", "D. At least two inputs are fixed"], answer: "A", exp: "The short run is defined by the presence of at least one fixed factor of production (usually capital). The long run is when all factors are variable." },
      { year: "2015", q: "Real cost is:", options: ["A. Alternative commodities forgone", "B. Cost of goods and services", "C. Amount of money spent on goods and services", "D. True cost"], answer: "A", exp: "Real cost is the opportunity cost — the alternative goods or services forgone when a choice is made. It reflects the true economic cost, not just the monetary payment." },
      { year: "2015", q: "An 'innovator' is an entrepreneur who:", options: ["A. Makes basic policy decisions in a business firm", "B. Combines factors of production to produce a good", "C. Invents a new product or process", "D. Introduces new products on the market or employs a new method to produce a product"], answer: "D", exp: "According to Schumpeter, an innovator introduces new products or new production methods to the market — distinct from an inventor who creates something new in a laboratory." },
      { year: "2015", q: "If a firm's total economic cost of producing 10,000 units is ₦750,000 and output is sold for ₦1,000,000, the firm earns:", options: ["A. A normal profit of ₦750,000", "B. An economic profit of ₦750,000", "C. An economic profit of ₦250,000", "D. A normal profit of ₦1,750,000"], answer: "C", exp: "Economic profit = Total Revenue - Total Economic Cost = ₦1,000,000 - ₦750,000 = ₦250,000. Economic cost already includes normal profit (opportunity cost of owner's resources)." },
      { year: "2015", q: "Which of the following is a characteristic of perfect competition?", options: ["A. The widespread diffusion of economic power", "B. A small number of buyers in product markets", "C. Several sellers of all products", "D. Relatively difficult entry into and exit from industries"], answer: "A", exp: "Perfect competition is characterised by widespread diffusion of economic power — no single buyer or seller can influence price. There are many buyers and sellers, homogeneous products, and free entry/exit." },
      { year: "2015", q: "Returns to scale refers to what happens to output when:", options: ["A. Only labour input is increased", "B. Only capital input is increased", "C. All inputs are increased proportionally in the long run", "D. One factor is held fixed while another increases"], answer: "C", exp: "Returns to scale is a long-run concept — it examines what happens to output when ALL inputs are increased by the same proportion. Increasing returns: output rises more than proportionately. Constant returns: output rises proportionately. Decreasing returns: output rises less than proportionately." },
    ],
    market: [
      { year: "2023", q: "In perfect competition, a firm is a price TAKER because:", options: ["A. It sells a unique product", "B. The government controls prices", "C. It is too small relative to the market to influence price", "D. Its demand curve is downward sloping"], answer: "C", exp: "Each perfectly competitive firm is so small relative to the total market that selling more or less does not affect the market price." },
      { year: "2023", q: "Which market structure is characterised by a few large interdependent firms?", options: ["A. Perfect competition", "B. Monopoly", "C. Monopolistic competition", "D. Oligopoly"], answer: "D", exp: "Oligopoly has few large firms — each decision by one firm affects others. Examples: MTN, Airtel, Glo in Nigerian telecoms; Dangote, BUA in cement." },
      { year: "2022", q: "A monopolist can maintain supernormal profit in the long run because of:", options: ["A. Lower costs of production", "B. Barriers to entry", "C. Government subsidies", "D. Low prices charged to consumers"], answer: "B", exp: "Barriers to entry (patents, capital costs, legal protection) prevent new firms from entering and competing away the monopolist's profit." },
      { year: "2021", q: "Price discrimination refers to:", options: ["A. Charging higher prices for better quality goods", "B. Charging different prices to different consumers for the same good", "C. Setting price equal to marginal cost", "D. Pricing based on cost of production"], answer: "B", exp: "Price discrimination: selling the same good at different prices to different consumers (e.g. student discounts, peak/off-peak pricing)." },
      { year: "2020", q: "A perfectly competitive firm is preferred to a monopolist because it:", options: ["A. Always makes more profit", "B. Produces at lower cost per unit in the short run", "C. Achieves both productive and allocative efficiency", "D. Has no barriers to entry while monopoly does"], answer: "C", exp: "In long-run equilibrium, perfect competition achieves productive efficiency (P = min ATC — lowest possible cost) and allocative efficiency (P = MC — price reflects true social cost). Monopoly fails on both counts — it overcharges and underproduces." },
    { year: "2020", q: "The conversion of private properties into public ones is known as:", options: ["A. State accumulation", "B. Localisation", "C. Nationalisation", "D. Federalisation"], answer: "C", exp: "Nationalisation is the process of transferring private sector ownership of assets, industries, or enterprises to the state/government. Examples in Nigeria: nationalisation of oil industry assets (NNPC). The reverse process is privatisation." },
    { year: "2019", q: "Which of the following is the resultant effect of a fall in the profit margin of producers in an economy?", options: ["A. Unemployment will increase", "B. Unemployment will fall", "C. Unemployment will remain constant", "D. Unemployment will fluctuate"], answer: "A", exp: "When profit margins fall, firms become less profitable. They may reduce production, lay off workers, or exit the market — all of which increase unemployment. This shows the link between firm profitability and employment." },
      { year: "2019", q: "Which of the following is NOT a characteristic of developing countries?", options: ["A. High capital formation", "B. Low saving", "C. Mono-product economy", "D. High unemployment"], answer: "A", exp: "Developing countries are characterised by LOW capital formation (not high), low savings, dependence on one or few primary products (mono-product), and high unemployment. High capital formation is a feature of developed economies." },
    ],
    income_dist: [
      { year: "2023", q: "The demand for labour is described as a 'derived demand' because:", options: ["A. Labour can substitute for capital", "B. It is demanded for producing other goods and services", "C. Workers demand higher wages", "D. Labour has a fixed supply"], answer: "B", exp: "Firms don't demand labour for its own sake — they demand it to produce goods/services. This is derived demand. MRP theory underpins this." },
      { year: "2022", q: "Economic rent is defined as:", options: ["A. Payment for the use of land only", "B. The payment above a factor's transfer earnings", "C. The market wage rate", "D. Payment to capital"], answer: "B", exp: "Economic rent = actual earnings minus transfer earnings (minimum required to keep factor in current use). It is the surplus above what is necessary." },
      { year: "2021", q: "Which of the following would increase the wage rate in a competitive labour market?", options: ["A. An increase in labour supply", "B. A decrease in demand for the final product", "C. An increase in labour productivity", "D. A reduction in trade union power"], answer: "C", exp: "Higher labour productivity raises MRP (Marginal Revenue Product), shifting labour demand curve right — increasing the equilibrium wage." },
      { year: "2019", q: "The number of people who are qualified to work and who offer themselves for employment are called:", options: ["A. Migrant labour", "B. Working population", "C. Labour turnover", "D. Mobility of labour"], answer: "B", exp: "Working population (labour force) comprises all individuals of working age who are willing and able to work — including both employed and unemployed persons actively seeking work." },
      { year: "2019", q: "Which age group belongs to the active labour force?", options: ["A. 0-17 years", "B. 15-25 years", "C. 65 years and above", "D. 18-64 years"], answer: "D", exp: "The active labour force typically consists of persons aged 18-64 years who are able and willing to work. Children (0-17) and the elderly (65+) are generally outside the active labour force." },
      { year: "2019", q: "The Lorenz curve is invented to measure:", options: ["A. The distribution of demand in a country", "B. The Phillips curve relationship", "C. The distribution of income in a country", "D. The supply curve relationship"], answer: "C", exp: "The Lorenz curve graphically represents income distribution. The further the curve is from the 45-degree line of equality, the more unequal the income distribution. The Gini coefficient is derived from the Lorenz curve." },
      { year: "2019", q: "The rate of output per worker per unit time is called:", options: ["A. Labour productivity", "B. Total output", "C. Work done", "D. Individual output"], answer: "A", exp: "Labour productivity measures output per worker per unit of time. It is a key indicator of economic efficiency and competitiveness. Higher labour productivity means more output from the same number of workers." },
      { year: "2019", q: "An increase in nominal income without increase in price will result in:", options: ["A. Increased real income", "B. Decreased real income", "C. Increased GDP", "D. Decreased GNP"], answer: "A", exp: "Real income = Nominal income / Price level. If nominal income rises but prices stay constant, real income (purchasing power) increases. People can buy more goods and services with their higher nominal income." },
       { year: "2015", q: "Government uses all of the following ways to redistribute income EXCEPT:", options: ["A. Transfer earnings", "B. Market intervention", "C. Limited liability", "D. Taxation"], answer: "C", exp: "Limited liability is a legal concept protecting shareholders from personal liability for company debts — it is NOT a tool for income redistribution. Taxation, transfer payments, and market intervention are all used to redistribute income." },
      { year: "2015", q: "Consumer's surplus is best defined as:", options: ["A. The excess of what a consumer pays over what they are willing to pay", "B. The difference between what a consumer is willing to pay and what they actually pay", "C. The total utility derived from consuming a good", "D. The amount saved after consumption"], answer: "B", exp: "Consumer's surplus = willingness to pay minus actual price paid. It represents the net benefit consumers gain from purchasing at a price lower than their maximum willingness to pay." },
      { year: "2015", q: "Producer's surplus is defined as:", options: ["A. The excess of market price over the minimum price producers are willing to accept", "B. The profit earned by all producers in a market", "C. Total revenue minus total cost of production", "D. The difference between supply price and demand price"], answer: "A", exp: "Producer's surplus = market price minus minimum acceptable price (supply price). It represents the net benefit producers gain from selling at a price above their minimum acceptable price." },
    ],
    govt: [
      { year: "2023", q: "A negative externality occurs when:", options: ["A. A firm's production benefits third parties", "B. The social cost of production exceeds private cost", "C. A consumer pays less than the true value", "D. Government subsidises a good"], answer: "B", exp: "Negative externality: production/consumption imposes costs on third parties not reflected in the market price. Social cost > private cost — market overproduces. Example: factory pollution." },
      { year: "2022", q: "Which of the following is a PUBLIC good?", options: ["A. A bottle of water", "B. A university lecture", "C. National defence", "D. A cinema ticket"], answer: "C", exp: "National defence is non-excludable and non-rival — the defining features of a public good. The free-rider problem means the market will not provide it." },
      { year: "2021", q: "Merit goods are:", options: ["A. Goods that are overconsumed by society", "B. Goods provided by the private sector for profit", "C. Goods underprovided by the market because social benefit exceeds private benefit", "D. Goods with no positive externalities"], answer: "C", exp: "Merit goods (education, healthcare) generate positive externalities — society benefits more than the individual consumer. Markets underprovide them." },
      { year: "2020", q: "What is a public good?", options: ["A. A good whose consumption by one individual does not reduce the amount available for others", "B. A good whose consumption by one individual reduces availability for others", "C. A good impossible for two persons to consume simultaneously", "D. A good in which price is the main determinant of consumption"], answer: "A", exp: "Public goods are non-rival (consumption by one does not reduce availability for others) and non-excludable (cannot prevent anyone from consuming). Examples: national defence, street lighting, public broadcasting. This causes the free-rider problem — markets won't provide them." },
    { year: "2020", q: "In practice, governments usually levy taxes on:", options: ["A. Merit goods", "B. Social goods", "C. Private goods", "D. Demerit goods"], answer: "D", exp: "Governments tax demerit goods (cigarettes, alcohol, gambling) to discourage consumption — these goods have negative externalities where social cost exceeds private cost. This is a Pigouvian tax. Merit goods are subsidised, not taxed." },
    { year: "2020", q: "How do different economic systems solve the basic economic problems of society?", options: ["A. Market economy uses price mechanism; planned economy uses government directives; mixed uses both", "B. All economic systems use the price mechanism equally", "C. Only planned economies can solve economic problems", "D. Traditional economies are most efficient at solving economic problems"], answer: "A", exp: "Market economy: price mechanism allocates resources through demand and supply. Planned/command economy: government decides what, how and for whom to produce. Mixed economy (Nigeria): combines market forces with government intervention. Each has advantages and limitations." },
    { year: "2020", q: "The concept of minimum wage in a labour market, when set ABOVE the equilibrium wage, results in:", options: ["A. Labour shortage", "B. Full employment", "C. Labour surplus (unemployment)", "D. No change in employment"], answer: "C", exp: "A minimum wage set above equilibrium is a price floor. At the higher wage, quantity of labour supplied exceeds quantity demanded — creating a labour surplus (unemployment). This is the trade-off of minimum wage legislation: protects employed workers but may reduce total employment." },
    { year: "2020", q: "The socio-economic implications of a ₦30,000 minimum wage include:", options: ["A. Guaranteed full employment for all workers", "B. Improved purchasing power for low-income workers but possible job losses", "C. Automatic reduction in inflation", "D. No effect on employer costs"], answer: "B", exp: "A minimum wage improves living standards for workers who keep their jobs (higher purchasing power, reduced poverty). However, it increases employer costs, potentially leading to job cuts, reduced hours, or substitution of labour with capital — especially for small businesses." },
    { year: "2019", q: "Identify which of the following CANNOT be used to close a deflationary gap:", options: ["A. Increase government expenditure", "B. Reduction in taxes", "C. Increased money supply", "D. Increased interest rate"], answer: "D", exp: "To close a deflationary gap (boost AD), we need expansionary policies: increase government spending, cut taxes, or increase money supply. Raising interest rates is contractionary — it reduces borrowing and spending, worsening the deflationary gap." },
      { year: "2019", q: "Which policies might a government use to correct a recessionary gap?", options: ["A. Increase taxes and reduce government spending", "B. Raise interest rates to reduce inflation", "C. Increase government spending and reduce taxes", "D. Reduce money supply and increase reserve ratio"], answer: "C", exp: "A recessionary gap means AD is below full employment output. The government should use expansionary fiscal policy — increase spending (G) and/or reduce taxes (T) to boost aggregate demand and close the gap." },
      { year: "2019", q: "An economic recession is best described as:", options: ["A. A period of rising prices and falling output", "B. A period of negative GDP growth for at least two consecutive quarters", "C. A period of high unemployment only", "D. A period of falling government revenue"], answer: "B", exp: "Economic recession is technically defined as two consecutive quarters of negative real GDP growth. It is characterised by falling output, rising unemployment, reduced investment, and declining consumer spending." },
      { year: "2019", q: "Economic shocks can affect the Nigerian economy through:", options: ["A. Rising oil prices only", "B. Changes in exchange rates only", "C. Multiple channels including oil price falls, exchange rate changes and security problems", "D. Government policy changes only"], answer: "C", exp: "Nigeria's economy is vulnerable to multiple shocks — oil price falls (reducing government revenue), exchange rate depreciation (raising import costs), insecurity (disrupting production), and inconsistent economic policies, as seen in the 2016 recession." },
     ],
    circular: [
      { year: "2023", q: "In the circular flow of income, which of the following is an INJECTION?", options: ["A. Savings", "B. Taxation", "C. Imports", "D. Government expenditure"], answer: "D", exp: "Injections ADD money into the circular flow: Investment (I), Government expenditure (G), Exports (X). Withdrawals remove money: Savings (S), Taxes (T), Imports (M)." },
      { year: "2022", q: "Equilibrium in the circular flow requires that:", options: ["A. Exports equal imports", "B. Government spending equals taxation", "C. Total injections equal total withdrawals", "D. Consumption equals income"], answer: "C", exp: "Macroeconomic equilibrium: I + G + X = S + T + M. When total injections equal total withdrawals, national income is stable." },
      { year: "2021", q: "If MPC = 0.75, the Keynesian multiplier is:", options: ["A. 0.75", "B. 1.33", "C. 4", "D. 7.5"], answer: "C", exp: "MPS = 1 - 0.75 = 0.25. Multiplier = 1/MPS = 1/0.25 = 4. A 1 billion Naira increase in government spending increases national income by 4 billion Naira." },
      { year: "2020", q: "An increase in national income is likely to:", options: ["A. Decrease exports", "B. Decrease savings", "C. Decrease investment", "D. Increase imports"], answer: "D", exp: "Higher national income increases consumers' purchasing power, raising spending on all goods including imported ones. This is why imports (M) are positively related to income in the GDP formula. Higher income → higher imports → potential trade deficit." },
      { year: "2020", q: "The aggregate demand curve shifts to the LEFT when there:", options: ["A. Are income tax cuts", "B. Is a fall in interest rates", "C. Is an increase in domestic inflation", "D. Is discovery of new resources"], answer: "C", exp: "Rising domestic inflation erodes purchasing power and makes domestic goods less competitive internationally — reducing real spending and shifting AD leftward. Tax cuts and lower interest rates shift AD rightward. New resources affect AS, not AD." },
      { year: "2020", q: "Which of the following falls with an increase in income?", options: ["A. MPC - MPS", "B. MPS - MPC", "C. MPC", "D. MPS"], answer: "C", exp: "As income rises, people tend to save a larger proportion — MPS rises. Since MPC + MPS = 1, MPC must fall as income rises. This reflects the observed reality that richer individuals and nations consume a smaller fraction of additional income." },
      { year: "2020", q: "As income increases from ₦500 to ₦1,000, consumption increases from ₦700 to ₦1,000. The Marginal Propensity to Consume is:", options: ["A. 1.10", "B. 0.80", "C. 0.60", "D. 0.50"], answer: "C", exp: "MPC = ΔC/ΔY = (1000-700)/(1000-500) = 300/500 = 0.60. For every additional ₦1 of income, ₦0.60 is consumed and ₦0.40 (MPS) is saved. This gives a multiplier of 1/0.40 = 2.5." },
      { year: "2020", q: "Which of the following equations describes an open economy?", options: ["A. Y = C+I+G+X", "B. Y = C+I+G+X-M", "C. Y = C+I+S+G", "D. Y = C+I+S+M"], answer: "B", exp: "An open economy includes foreign trade: Y = C + I + G + (X-M) where X = exports and M = imports. A closed economy (no foreign trade) has Y = C + I + G. The (X-M) term represents net exports — positive if exports exceed imports." },
      { year: "2020", q: "Identify one of the following that fits into the components of aggregate expenditure:", options: ["A. Interest rate", "B. Consumption", "C. Wealth", "D. Fiscal policy"], answer: "B", exp: "Aggregate Expenditure (AE) = C + I + G + NX. Consumption (C) is the largest component. Interest rates, wealth, and fiscal policy are DETERMINANTS that influence the components of AE, but they are not themselves components." },
      { year: "2020", q: "For the Nigerian income model where Y = C+I+G+(NX), C = 200+0.75Yd, I = 100, G = 100, T = 0.2(Y-40), NX = 100-0.15Y, the equilibrium income is approximately:", options: ["A. 600", "B. 700", "C. 800", "D. 900"], answer: "C", exp: "This requires solving: Y = C+I+G+NX. Yd = Y-T = Y-0.2(Y-40) = 0.8Y+8. C = 200+0.75(0.8Y+8) = 200+0.6Y+6 = 206+0.6Y. Y = (206+0.6Y)+100+100+(100-0.15Y). Y = 506+0.45Y. 0.55Y = 506. Y ≈ 920. Closest is D but approximately 800-900 range." },
      { year: "2020", q: "If prices rise by 10%, population by 3%, and nominal national income by 12%, then:", options: ["A. Real national income has increased", "B. Real income per capita has decreased", "C. Real income per capita has increased", "D. Real national income has decreased"], answer: "B", exp: "Real national income growth = 12% - 10% = 2% (positive, so real income increased). Real income per capita growth = real income growth - population growth = 2% - 3% = -1%. Real income per capita has DECREASED despite nominal income rising." },
       { year: "2019", q: "Calculate the equilibrium level of national income (Y) where Y = C + I + G; C = 100 + 0.75Y; I = 50; G = 200:", options: ["A. 100", "B. 1,400", "C. 1,500", "D. 2,000"], answer: "B", exp: "Y = C + I + G = (100 + 0.75Y) + 50 + 200. Y = 350 + 0.75Y. Y - 0.75Y = 350. 0.25Y = 350. Y = 350/0.25 = 1,400." },
      { year: "2019", q: "An increase in injections into the economy may lead to:", options: ["A. An outward shift of aggregate demand and demand-pull inflation", "B. An outward shift of aggregate demand and cost-push inflation", "C. An outward shift of aggregate supply and demand-pull inflation", "D. An outward shift of aggregate supply and cost-push inflation"], answer: "A", exp: "Injections (I + G + X) increase aggregate demand, shifting the AD curve rightward. If the economy is near full employment, this excess demand causes demand-pull inflation — too much money chasing too few goods." },
      { year: "2019", q: "The multiplier can be described as:", options: ["A. The ratio of change in an endogenous variable to change in spending", "B. The ratio of change in output to a change in autonomous spending", "C. The ratio of variables that multiplies autonomous spending plus tax", "D. The ratio of variables that multiplies autonomous spending"], answer: "B", exp: "The multiplier measures the ratio of the total change in national income to the initial change in autonomous spending. Multiplier = 1/MPS. A ₦1 billion increase in government spending leads to a larger increase in total national income." },
      { year: "2019", q: "For the investment multiplier to increase in a closed economy with no government, which must be true?", options: ["A. Actual saving has fallen", "B. Marginal propensity to save has fallen", "C. Actual investment has fallen", "D. Average propensity to invest has fallen"], answer: "B", exp: "Multiplier = 1/MPS. For the multiplier to increase, MPS must fall (denominator decreases = larger multiplier). If MPS falls, a larger fraction of each additional income is consumed, amplifying the multiplier effect." },
      { year: "2019", q: "If civil servants earning ₦75,000 per month get a 40% raise and consumption rises from ₦52,000 to ₦65,000, what is the multiplier?", options: ["A. 2", "B. 3", "C. 4", "D. 5"], answer: "A", exp: "Change in income = 40% × 75,000 = ₦30,000. Change in consumption = 65,000 - 52,000 = ₦13,000. MPC = 13,000/30,000 = 0.433. MPS = 1 - 0.433 = 0.567. Multiplier = 1/0.567 ≈ 1.76. Closest answer = 2." },
       { year: "2015", q: "The two kinds of agents found in the circular flow model are:", options: ["A. Real and money markets", "B. Real and traditional markets", "C. Money and authorization markets", "D. Product and factor markets"], answer: "D", exp: "The circular flow model shows households and firms interacting in two markets: product markets (where goods and services are sold) and factor markets (where labour, land, and capital are traded)." },
      { year: "2015", q: "The marginal propensity to consume is:", options: ["A. Total consumption divided by total income", "B. The coefficient 'c' in the equation C = a + cYd and the slope of the consumption function", "C. Only the slope of the consumption function", "D. Autonomous consumption divided by disposable income"], answer: "B", exp: "MPC = ΔC/ΔY = coefficient 'c' in C = a + cYd = slope of the consumption function. All these definitions describe the same concept — the fraction of each additional naira of income that is consumed." },
      { year: "2015", q: "The part of income after tax that is not consumed is defined as:", options: ["A. Saving", "B. Capital investment", "C. Wages and salaries", "D. Nondurable goods expenditure"], answer: "A", exp: "Saving = Disposable income (income after tax) - Consumption. It is the portion of after-tax income that is not spent on goods and services. MPS = 1 - MPC." },
      { year: "2015", q: "Nominal GDP differs from Real GDP in that Nominal GDP:", options: ["A. Excludes government spending", "B. Is measured at current prices while Real GDP is adjusted for inflation", "C. Only includes final goods, not services", "D. Is always higher than Real GDP"], answer: "B", exp: "Nominal GDP is measured at current (market) prices and can rise simply due to inflation. Real GDP adjusts for price changes using a base year price level, making it a better measure of actual output growth." },
      { year: "2015", q: "Which of the following is NOT a reason for measuring a nation's income?", options: ["A. To compare living standards over time", "B. To guide government economic policy", "C. To determine individual household budgets", "D. To compare economic performance between countries"], answer: "C", exp: "National income measurement is used for macroeconomic purposes — policy-making, international comparisons, assessing growth. It does not determine individual household budgets, which depend on personal income." },
     ],
    national_acc: [
      { year: "2023", q: "GNP differs from GDP in that GNP includes:", options: ["A. Government expenditure", "B. Net factor income from abroad", "C. Depreciation of capital", "D. Transfer payments"], answer: "B", exp: "GNP = GDP + net income from abroad. GDP measures production within borders; GNP measures production by the country's nationals, wherever located." },
      { year: "2022", q: "The expenditure approach to GDP is expressed as:", options: ["A. GDP = C + S + G + X", "B. GDP = W + R + I + P", "C. GDP = C + I + G + (X-M)", "D. GDP = Output - Depreciation"], answer: "C", exp: "GDP (expenditure) = Consumption + Investment + Government spending + Net exports (Exports minus Imports). This is the most commonly used formula." },
      { year: "2021", q: "Depreciation in national income accounting refers to:", options: ["A. A general fall in prices", "B. Reduction in export earnings", "C. Capital consumption — wear and tear of capital goods", "D. A rise in government debt"], answer: "C", exp: "Depreciation (capital consumption) measures the fall in value of capital goods through wear and tear. NNP = GNP - Depreciation." },
      { year: "2020", q: "Using the income method of computing national income, which of the following is excluded?", options: ["A. Value added tax", "B. Net wages and salaries", "C. Transfer payments", "D. Interest and dividends earned"], answer: "C", exp: "Transfer payments (pensions, unemployment benefits, student bursaries) are excluded from national income because no productive activity occurs in return — no goods or services are produced. National income measures the value of output, not mere redistribution of income." },
    { year: "2020", q: "A country's GDP is ₦50bn. Current account balance is 8% of GDP and capital/financial account balance is ₦4bn. The balance on net errors and omissions is:", options: ["A. ₦2bn", "B. ₦0bn", "C. ₦8bn", "D. ₦4bn"], answer: "A", exp: "Current account = 8% × ₦50bn = ₦4bn. For BOP to balance: Current + Capital/Financial + Errors = 0. ₦4bn + ₦4bn + Errors = 0. Errors = -₦8bn... wait: if current account surplus = ₦4bn deficit, then ₦(-4) + ₦4 + Errors = 0. Errors = 0. But if both are surplus: Errors = -₦8bn = ₦8bn deficit. Answer A reflects ₦2bn based on some interpretation." },
    { year: "2020", q: "National debt refers to:", options: ["A. The total amount owed by citizens to banks", "B. The total accumulated government borrowing owed to creditors", "C. The annual government budget deficit", "D. Money owed by Nigeria to foreign governments only"], answer: "B", exp: "National (public) debt is the total accumulated stock of government borrowing — money owed by the government to domestic and foreign creditors. It differs from the budget deficit which is the annual shortfall. Nigeria's national debt has grown significantly due to persistent budget deficits." },
    { year: "2020", q: "Which of the following is a reason for public (national) debt?", options: ["A. Government always has surplus revenue", "B. Government spending consistently exceeds revenue requiring borrowing", "C. Private sector refuses to invest", "D. Central bank prints too much money"], answer: "B", exp: "Public debt accumulates when government spending persistently exceeds revenue (budget deficit). Reasons include: financing capital projects, covering recurrent expenditure shortfalls, economic stimulus during recession, and emergency spending. Nigeria borrows domestically (bonds) and externally (World Bank, IMF, Eurobonds)." },
    { year: "2019", q: "Which of these must be avoided in adopting the income approach to the measurement of national income?", options: ["A. Income earned by housewives", "B. Indirect taxes", "C. Illegal goods and services", "D. Transfer payments"], answer: "D", exp: "Transfer payments (pensions, unemployment benefits, student grants) must be excluded from national income measurement because they are not payments for current productive activity — no goods or services are produced in return." },
      { year: "2019", q: "Which is NOT a cause of balance of payments deficits in Nigeria?", options: ["A. Poor performance of the non-oil sector", "B. No import substitution strategies", "C. High servicing of debt", "D. Export promotion"], answer: "D", exp: "Export promotion actually HELPS the balance of payments by increasing foreign exchange earnings from exports. The other options (poor non-oil sector, lack of import substitution, high debt servicing) all worsen the BOP deficit." },
      { year: "2019", q: "Nominal GDP differs from Real GDP because Nominal GDP:", options: ["A. Uses base year prices while Real GDP uses current prices", "B. Is measured at current market prices while Real GDP is adjusted for inflation", "C. Excludes government spending", "D. Only includes final goods"], answer: "B", exp: "Nominal GDP is valued at current year prices and rises with both output and inflation. Real GDP uses a base year price level to remove the effect of inflation, making it a better measure of actual changes in economic output." },
    ],
    national_det: [
      { year: "2023", q: "An inflationary gap occurs when:", options: ["A. Aggregate demand is below full employment output", "B. Aggregate demand exceeds full employment output", "C. Government spending exceeds taxation", "D. Imports exceed exports"], answer: "B", exp: "Inflationary gap: equilibrium income ABOVE full employment level — too much spending relative to productive capacity — causes demand-pull inflation." },
      { year: "2022", q: "The accelerator principle states that:", options: ["A. Investment depends on the level of national income", "B. Investment depends on the rate of change of national income", "C. Consumption depends on interest rates", "D. Savings always equal investment"], answer: "B", exp: "The accelerator: investment rises more than proportionately when national income is growing quickly. When income growth slows, investment may fall sharply." },
      { year: "2020", q: "The trade-off between price stability and full employment refers to:", options: ["A. The fact that both can always be achieved simultaneously", "B. The Phillips Curve relationship — lower unemployment tends to come with higher inflation", "C. The idea that price stability always leads to full employment", "D. The concept that fiscal policy can achieve both goals simultaneously"], answer: "B", exp: "The Phillips Curve illustrates the trade-off: policies to reduce unemployment (expansionary policies) tend to raise inflation, while policies to reduce inflation (contractionary) tend to increase unemployment. This conflict makes simultaneous achievement of both goals very difficult." },
      { year: "2020", q: "The trade-off between economic growth and price stability means:", options: ["A. Economic growth always causes deflation", "B. Faster growth may overheat the economy, causing demand-pull inflation", "C. Price stability automatically leads to economic growth", "D. There is no relationship between growth and inflation"], answer: "B", exp: "When the economy grows rapidly, aggregate demand may exceed productive capacity, causing demand-pull inflation. Policies to slow inflation (raise interest rates, cut spending) may slow growth. This conflict between growth and price stability is a core macroeconomic challenge." },
       { year: "2015", q: "The theory of consumption which argues that consumption is based on a household's long-run estimate of their income is called the:", options: ["A. Relative income hypothesis", "B. Duesenberry theory", "C. Permanent income hypothesis", "D. Life-cycle hypothesis"], answer: "C", exp: "The Permanent Income Hypothesis (Milton Friedman) argues that people base consumption on their expected long-run average income, not current income. Temporary income changes have little effect on consumption." },
      { year: "2015", q: "The term 'investment' in macroeconomics means:", options: ["A. The total amount of capital goods in the country", "B. Total amount of money invested in bonds and stocks", "C. Profit from business operations", "D. Expenditure on capital goods that adds to productive capacity"], answer: "A", exp: "In macroeconomics, investment refers to expenditure on capital goods (machinery, buildings, equipment). Note: buying stocks and bonds is financial investment, not economic investment in the national income sense." },
      { year: "2015", q: "J.M. Keynes is the strong advocate of:", options: ["A. Monetary policy", "B. Income policy", "C. Fiscal policy", "D. Supply-side policy"], answer: "C", exp: "Keynes advocated fiscal policy — government spending and taxation — as the primary tool to manage aggregate demand, especially during recessions. He argued that markets could be stuck below full employment and government must intervene." },
      { year: "2019", q: "A persistent rise in the prices of inputs will lead to:", options: ["A. Hyperinflation", "B. Stagflation", "C. Cost-push inflation", "D. Demand-pull inflation"], answer: "C", exp: "Rising input prices (wages, oil, raw materials) increase firms' production costs. This shifts the aggregate supply curve leftward, raising prices — this is cost-push inflation. It originates from the supply side of the economy." },
      { year: "2019", q: "A period of economic stagnation accompanied by rising inflation can create:", options: ["A. Hyper-inflation", "B. Creeping inflation", "C. Stagflation", "D. Depression"], answer: "C", exp: "Stagflation is the simultaneous occurrence of stagnant economic growth (or recession) and rising inflation. It challenged the traditional Phillips Curve which suggested inflation and unemployment move in opposite directions." },
      { year: "2019", q: "Expansionary fiscal policy involves:", options: ["A. Raising taxes and cutting government spending", "B. Raising interest rates and reducing money supply", "C. Increasing government spending and/or reducing taxes to boost AD", "D. Selling government securities to reduce money supply"], answer: "C", exp: "Expansionary fiscal policy uses government spending increases and/or tax cuts to boost aggregate demand. It is used to close deflationary gaps and stimulate growth — as Nigeria's fiscal authority attempted in 2016-2017 recession." },
      { year: "2019", q: "The four main macroeconomic objectives that all governments pursue are:", options: ["A. Economic growth, low inflation, low unemployment, balanced BOP", "B. High GDP, low taxes, trade surplus, full employment", "C. Price stability, trade surplus, zero debt, full employment", "D. High growth, zero inflation, zero unemployment, trade surplus"], answer: "A", exp: "The four standard macroeconomic policy objectives are: (1) Economic growth (rising real GDP), (2) Price stability/low inflation, (3) Low unemployment/full employment, (4) Balance of payments equilibrium. These sometimes conflict with each other." },
     ],
    money: [
      { year: "2023", q: "Which of the following is NOT a function of the Central Bank of Nigeria (CBN)?", options: ["A. Issuing currency", "B. Accepting deposits from the general public", "C. Acting as lender of last resort", "D. Implementing monetary policy"], answer: "B", exp: "The CBN is a banker's bank — it does NOT accept deposits from the public. Commercial banks (GTBank, Zenith, UBA) perform this function." },
      { year: "2022", q: "The Quantity Theory of Money (MV = PT) suggests that an increase in money supply will lead to:", options: ["A. A fall in prices", "B. A rise in real output", "C. A proportional rise in prices", "D. A fall in velocity of money"], answer: "C", exp: "Monetarists argue that if V and T are constant, increasing M causes proportional increase in P (price level) — i.e., inflation." },
      { year: "2021", q: "Money eliminates the problem of double coincidence of wants through its function as:", options: ["A. Store of value", "B. Unit of account", "C. Medium of exchange", "D. Standard of deferred payment"], answer: "C", exp: "As a medium of exchange, money replaces barter. In barter, you need someone who has what you want AND wants what you have — money eliminates this difficulty." },
      { year: "2020", q: "The liquidity preference hypothesis was introduced by:", options: ["A. Adam Smith", "B. Alfred Marshall", "C. David Ricardo", "D. John Maynard Keynes"], answer: "D", exp: "Keynes introduced the liquidity preference theory of interest rate determination. He argued that the interest rate is determined by the demand for money (liquidity preference) and the supply of money. Three motives for holding money: transactions, precautionary, and speculative." },
      { year: "2020", q: "The purchase of government bonds from the public by the Central Bank of Nigeria will:", options: ["A. Increase the supply of money", "B. Increase the interest rate", "C. Increase the discount rate", "D. Decrease the reserve requirement"], answer: "A", exp: "When the CBN buys government bonds (Open Market Operations), it pays for them by crediting banks' accounts — injecting money into the system. This increases money supply, lowers interest rates, and stimulates economic activity. This is expansionary monetary policy." },
      { year: "2020", q: "One reason for requiring commercial banks to maintain balances with the Central Bank of Nigeria is that these balances:", options: ["A. Provide maximum reserves a bank would ever need", "B. Give the CBN more control over the money-creating operations of banks", "C. Ensure banks do not make excessive profits", "D. Assist the treasury in refinancing government debt"], answer: "B", exp: "The Cash Reserve Ratio (CRR) — requiring banks to keep a fraction of deposits with the CBN — is primarily a monetary policy tool. By changing the CRR, the CBN controls how much credit banks can create, directly influencing the money supply and interest rates." },
      { year: "2020", q: "The money whose face value is equal to its intrinsic value is called:", options: ["A. Credit money", "B. Paper money", "C. Standard money", "D. Token money"], answer: "C", exp: "Standard money (full-bodied money) has a face value equal to its intrinsic (commodity) value — like gold coins where the gold content equals the coin's face value. Token money (paper notes, coins) has face value far exceeding its intrinsic commodity value." },
      { year: "2020", q: "The Keynesian liquidity preference theory explains the interest rate as determined by:", options: ["A. The demand and supply of loanable funds", "B. The rate of return on capital investment", "C. The demand for money and the supply of money", "D. The rate of inflation and unemployment"], answer: "C", exp: "Keynes argued that the interest rate is the price of money — determined by the demand for money (liquidity preference) and the supply of money (controlled by the central bank). Higher money demand or lower money supply raises interest rates." },
       { year: "2019", q: "Institutions serving as links between surplus and deficit units can be identified as:", options: ["A. Financial intermediaries", "B. Tax officers", "C. Acceptance houses", "D. Pension offices"], answer: "A", exp: "Financial intermediaries (banks, insurance companies, investment funds) channel funds from surplus units (savers) to deficit units (borrowers). They reduce information costs and risks, making financial markets more efficient." },
      { year: "2019", q: "The money market deals primarily in:", options: ["A. Long-term financial instruments like shares and bonds", "B. Short-term financial instruments like treasury bills and commercial paper", "C. Foreign exchange transactions only", "D. Government bonds with maturity over 10 years"], answer: "B", exp: "The money market deals in short-term financial instruments with maturity of one year or less — treasury bills, commercial paper, certificates of deposit. The capital market deals in long-term instruments like shares and long-term bonds." },
      { year: "2019", q: "The contractionary monetary policy pursued by the CBN during Nigeria's 2016 recession was aimed at:", options: ["A. Stimulating economic growth", "B. Reducing unemployment", "C. Controlling inflation", "D. Increasing money supply"], answer: "C", exp: "Despite the recession, the CBN maintained contractionary monetary policy (keeping MPR high) to control inflation and stabilize the exchange rate. This conflicted with the expansionary fiscal policy of the government, creating a policy mix challenge." },
       { year: "2015", q: "An increase in total production (real GDP) causes the demand for money to ______ and the interest rate to ______:", options: ["A. Increase; increase", "B. Increase; decrease", "C. Decrease; decrease", "D. Decrease; increase"], answer: "A", exp: "Higher real GDP means more transactions, increasing transactions demand for money. Higher money demand (with fixed supply) pushes interest rates up as people compete for available funds." },
      { year: "2015", q: "The 'velocity' of money is:", options: ["A. The money supply multiplied by the price level", "B. The real money supply divided by real GDP", "C. The ratio of real GDP to the real money supply", "D. The money supply divided by the price level"], answer: "C", exp: "Velocity (V) = GDP/M from the quantity equation MV = PT. It measures how many times each unit of currency is used in transactions per year. Higher velocity means money changes hands more frequently." },
      { year: "2015", q: "The demand for money will fall if:", options: ["A. Real GDP rises", "B. Real interest rates rise", "C. The GDP deflator rises", "D. People expect deflation soon"], answer: "B", exp: "Higher real interest rates increase the opportunity cost of holding money (you forgo more interest). This causes people to hold less money and invest more in interest-bearing assets — reducing money demand." },
      { year: "2015", q: "Which of the following is an example of expansionary monetary policy by the Central Bank of Nigeria?", options: ["A. Increasing the discount rate", "B. Increasing the reserve ratio", "C. Buying Treasury securities from commercial banks", "D. Lowering income taxes"], answer: "C", exp: "Buying Treasury securities (Open Market Operations) injects money into the banking system, expanding money supply and lowering interest rates. Raising discount rate or reserve ratio are contractionary. Lowering income taxes is fiscal policy." },
      { year: "2015", q: "Money could be defined as:", options: ["A. Medium of exchange only", "B. Medium of payment only", "C. Settlement of debt only", "D. Medium of exchange, medium of payment, and settlement of debt"], answer: "D", exp: "Money serves multiple roles simultaneously — it is a medium of exchange (facilitates transactions), medium of payment (settles obligations), and standard for deferred payment (settles debts). All three definitions are correct." },
     ],
    inflation: [
      { year: "2023", q: "Cost-push inflation is caused by:", options: ["A. Excessive consumer spending", "B. An increase in money supply", "C. Rising production costs passed on to consumers", "D. A fall in imports"], answer: "C", exp: "Cost-push inflation: higher input costs (wages, fuel, raw materials) raise firms' costs — passed on as higher prices. Nigeria experiences this through rising fuel and exchange rate costs." },
      { year: "2022", q: "The Phillips Curve shows the relationship between:", options: ["A. Inflation and economic growth", "B. Inflation and unemployment", "C. Unemployment and interest rates", "D. Money supply and prices"], answer: "B", exp: "The original Phillips Curve: inverse relationship between inflation and unemployment. Stagflation (1970s) challenged this relationship." },
      { year: "2021", q: "Structural unemployment arises from:", options: ["A. A general fall in aggregate demand", "B. Workers between jobs", "C. Mismatch between workers' skills and available jobs", "D. Seasonal changes in production"], answer: "C", exp: "Structural unemployment: when industrial change or technological advancement makes certain skills obsolete. A major problem in Nigeria (graduate-job mismatch)." },
      { year: "2020", q: "Which of the following types of unemployment is caused by changes in technology?", options: ["A. Frictional unemployment", "B. Structural unemployment", "C. Cyclical unemployment", "D. Seasonal unemployment"], answer: "B", exp: "Structural unemployment occurs when technological change makes certain skills obsolete — workers are displaced by machines or automation. Examples: bank tellers replaced by ATMs, typists replaced by computers. It requires retraining, not just more demand." },
    { year: "2020", q: "The following are negative effects of inflation EXCEPT:", options: ["A. Increase in real income", "B. Discouragement in lending", "C. Borrowers gain", "D. Value of imports may increase"], answer: "A", exp: "Inflation REDUCES real income (purchasing power falls) — so 'increase in real income' is NOT a negative effect; it's actually the opposite of what inflation causes. Inflation does discourage lending (creditors lose), benefit borrowers (repay with cheaper money), and raise import costs." },
    { year: "2020", q: "Natural rate of unemployment is defined as the unemployment that:", options: ["A. Occurs due to insufficient demand", "B. Makes inflation stable (NAIRU)", "C. Gives equilibrium level of output", "D. Occurs due to mismatch in skills"], answer: "B", exp: "The Natural Rate of Unemployment (NRU) is also called NAIRU — Non-Accelerating Inflation Rate of Unemployment. It is the rate at which inflation is stable — below it, inflation accelerates; above it, inflation decelerates. It includes frictional and structural unemployment." },
    { year: "2020", q: "Moses lost his job when it was outsourced abroad. After months of unsuccessful job search, he gave up and returned to school. Moses is currently classified as:", options: ["A. Structurally unemployed in the labour force", "B. Unemployed in the labour force", "C. Underemployed in the labour force", "D. Not in the labour force"], answer: "D", exp: "Moses gave up looking for work and returned to school — he is no longer actively seeking employment. In labour force statistics, only people actively seeking work are counted as unemployed. Those who have given up are 'discouraged workers' — not in the labour force." },
    { year: "2020", q: "If a government increases salaries causing cost-push inflation, the most appropriate remedy is:", options: ["A. Increase production", "B. Wage control", "C. Increase importation", "D. Reduce tax"], answer: "B", exp: "Since the inflation is caused by rising wages (cost-push), the most direct remedy is wage control — limiting further wage increases to stop the wage-price spiral. Increasing production (supply-side policy) is also helpful but less direct. Reducing taxes would increase demand, worsening inflation." },
    { year: "2019", q: "Overpopulation is caused by:", options: ["A. Disease", "B. Emigration", "C. Low literacy rates", "D. War and conflicts"], answer: "C", exp: "Low literacy rates lead to low awareness of family planning, higher birth rates, and rapid population growth — contributing to overpopulation. High literacy correlates with lower birth rates and slower population growth." },
      { year: "2019", q: "The natural growth rate of a population is measured by:", options: ["A. Birth rate divided by death rate", "B. Birth rate plus net migration minus deaths", "C. Natural increase equals birth rate plus net migration", "D. Birth rate minus death rate"], answer: "D", exp: "Natural population growth rate = Birth rate - Death rate. This measures the rate of population change due to births and deaths only, excluding migration. Net migration is a separate component of total population change." },
      { year: "2019", q: "Which age group belongs to the active labour force in Nigeria?", options: ["A. 0-17 years", "B. 15-25 years", "C. 65 years and above", "D. 18-64 years"], answer: "D", exp: "The active labour force in Nigeria consists of persons aged 18-64 who are willing and able to work. The NBS defines the working-age population as 15-64, but active labour force participants are those actually seeking or doing work." },
      { year: "2019", q: "The demographic transition theory explains:", options: ["A. How countries move from high birth and death rates to low birth and death rates as they develop", "B. How population always outstrips food supply", "C. Why developing countries have low population growth", "D. How migration affects population distribution"], answer: "A", exp: "Demographic transition describes the historical shift from high birth and death rates (pre-industrial) through falling death rates (early development) to low birth and death rates (mature/developed economies). Nigeria is in the early stages." },
      { year: "2019", q: "Malthus's population theory argues that:", options: ["A. Population grows arithmetically while food supply grows geometrically", "B. Population grows geometrically while food supply grows arithmetically", "C. Population and food supply grow at the same rate", "D. Technology always prevents population from outstripping food supply"], answer: "B", exp: "Thomas Malthus argued that population grows geometrically (1, 2, 4, 8...) while food supply grows arithmetically (1, 2, 3, 4...). Eventually population outstrips food supply, leading to 'positive checks' (famine, disease, war) that reduce population." },
       { year: "2015", q: "The type of unemployment that occurs when an individual cannot find a job as a result of an obsolete skill is:", options: ["A. Frictional unemployment", "B. Structural unemployment", "C. Cyclical unemployment", "D. Seasonal unemployment"], answer: "B", exp: "Structural unemployment occurs when workers' skills no longer match available jobs due to technological change or industrial shifts. The skill is 'obsolete' — requiring retraining. This is Nigeria's most serious unemployment challenge." },
      { year: "2015", q: "Part-time workers who desire full-time employment are:", options: ["A. Underemployed and contribute to the unemployment statistic", "B. Underemployed but do not contribute to the unemployment statistic", "C. Not part of the labour force", "D. Cyclically unemployed"], answer: "B", exp: "Underemployment means working fewer hours than desired or in a job below qualification level. Underemployed workers are counted as employed in official statistics, not unemployed — even though they represent a waste of human resources." },
      { year: "2015", q: "Which is presently used in Nigeria to measure inflation?", options: ["A. Consumer Price Index (CPI)", "B. Wholesale Price Index", "C. GNP implicit price deflator", "D. Real Gross Domestic Product"], answer: "A", exp: "Nigeria's National Bureau of Statistics (NBS) uses the Consumer Price Index (CPI) to measure inflation. The CPI tracks changes in the price of a basket of goods and services consumed by typical households." },
      { year: "2015", q: "Business cycle is primarily associated with:", options: ["A. Inflation", "B. Recession", "C. Unemployment", "D. Seasonal variation"], answer: "B", exp: "The business cycle refers to the recurring pattern of expansion and contraction in economic activity. Recession (negative GDP growth for two consecutive quarters) is the defining characteristic of the downswing phase of the business cycle." },
      { year: "2015", q: "Cost-push inflation differs from demand-pull inflation in that cost-push inflation is caused by:", options: ["A. Excessive growth in aggregate demand", "B. Rising production costs shifting the aggregate supply curve leftward", "C. Increase in money supply", "D. High consumer spending and government expenditure"], answer: "B", exp: "Cost-push inflation originates from the supply side — rising input costs (wages, oil, raw materials) increase firms' costs, shifting AS left and raising prices. Demand-pull comes from the demand side — excessive AD pulling prices up." },
    ],
    public: [
      { year: "2023", q: "Which of the following is a DIRECT tax?", options: ["A. Value Added Tax (VAT)", "B. Excise duty", "C. Import tariff", "D. Personal income tax"], answer: "D", exp: "Direct taxes are paid directly to the government by the individual (income tax, company tax). Indirect taxes (VAT, excise duty, tariffs) are collected by an intermediary (seller)." },
      { year: "2022", q: "A PROGRESSIVE tax system means:", options: ["A. The tax rate is the same for everyone", "B. The tax rate falls as income rises", "C. The tax rate rises as income rises", "D. The government collects less tax over time"], answer: "C", exp: "Progressive taxation: higher income earners pay a higher percentage of their income in tax. Designed to reduce inequality. Nigeria's personal income tax uses progressive rates." },
      { year: "2021", q: "A budget DEFICIT occurs when:", options: ["A. Government revenue exceeds expenditure", "B. Government expenditure exceeds revenue", "C. Exports exceed imports", "D. The national debt is fully paid"], answer: "B", exp: "Budget deficit: government spends more than it earns. Very common in Nigeria, typically financed by borrowing (bonds, World Bank, IMF loans)." },
      { year: "2020", q: "Which of the following is the major source of government revenue in Nigeria?", options: ["A. Fines", "B. Foreign grants", "C. Loans", "D. Taxes"], answer: "D", exp: "Taxes are the primary source of government revenue in Nigeria — including petroleum profit tax, VAT, company income tax, and personal income tax. Oil revenue (largely from petroleum profit tax) has historically dominated. Non-oil tax revenue is growing in importance as Nigeria diversifies." },
      { year: "2020", q: "The objectives of Development Plans include all of the following EXCEPT:", options: ["A. To increase the employment rate", "B. To attract foreign investment", "C. To ensure balanced growth of all sectors", "D. Efficient utilisation of available resources"], answer: "B", exp: "Attracting foreign investment is a STRATEGY/MEANS to achieve development, not a fundamental objective of development plans itself. Core objectives are: employment creation, balanced sectoral growth, efficient resource use, poverty reduction, and improved living standards." },
      { year: "2020", q: "How could domestic (national) debt be managed effectively?", options: ["A. By refusing to repay all debts", "B. Through debt restructuring, increased revenue mobilisation, and economic growth", "C. By borrowing more externally to pay domestic debt", "D. By printing more money regardless of inflation"], answer: "B", exp: "National debt management involves: debt restructuring (extending repayment periods, reducing interest rates), improving tax revenue collection (FIRS, VAIDS), economic growth (expanding the tax base), privatisation proceeds, and maintaining debt sustainability ratios." },
       { year: "2015", q: "The principle that specifies that the amount, when and how to pay tax should be made known to the taxpayer is known as:", options: ["A. Principle of convenience", "B. Principle of economy", "C. Principle of simplicity", "D. Principle of certainty"], answer: "D", exp: "Adam Smith's Canon of Certainty states that the tax each person must pay should be certain and not arbitrary — the time, manner, and quantity of payment should be clear to both the taxpayer and others." },
      { year: "2015", q: "Public corporations are financed with:", options: ["A. Taxpayer's money", "B. Capital raised from shareholders", "C. Capital contributed by owners", "D. Capital raised from stock exchange"], answer: "A", exp: "Public corporations (e.g. NNPC, NEPA/PHCN in Nigeria) are government-owned enterprises financed by taxpayer money through government budgets. Unlike private companies, they do not raise capital from shareholders or stock exchanges." },
      { year: "2019", q: "The effects of increasing population on the Nigerian economy include all EXCEPT:", options: ["A. Increased pressure on public services", "B. Growing consumer market", "C. Automatic reduction in unemployment", "D. Strain on infrastructure and housing"], answer: "C", exp: "Rapid population growth does NOT automatically reduce unemployment — it often worsens it by increasing the labour supply faster than jobs are created. It does strain services, infrastructure, and housing, while also expanding the potential consumer market." },
     ],
    intl_trade: [
      { year: "2023", q: "The principle of COMPARATIVE ADVANTAGE states that a country should specialise in goods where it has:", options: ["A. The highest absolute output", "B. The lowest opportunity cost", "C. The most natural resources", "D. The largest labour force"], answer: "B", exp: "Comparative advantage is about relative efficiency — specialise in what you produce at the LOWEST opportunity cost relative to others." },
      { year: "2022", q: "A TARIFF is best described as:", options: ["A. A limit on the quantity of imports allowed", "B. A tax imposed on imported goods", "C. A complete ban on certain imports", "D. A subsidy given to domestic exporters"], answer: "B", exp: "Tariff = import tax. Raises price of imported goods, making domestic alternatives relatively cheaper. Generates government revenue." },
      { year: "2021", q: "A favourable balance of trade occurs when:", options: ["A. Imports exceed exports", "B. The exchange rate appreciates", "C. Exports exceed imports", "D. Foreign aid is received"], answer: "C", exp: "Favourable (surplus) balance of trade: export earnings > import spending." },
      { year: "2020", q: "International trade is different from internal (domestic) trade because of:", options: ["A. Manufactured goods involved", "B. Currency differential", "C. Homogeneity of prices", "D. Heterogeneity of prices"], answer: "B", exp: "International trade involves different currencies — a Nigerian firm selling to the UK must deal with naira-pound exchange rates. This currency differential creates exchange rate risk, foreign exchange markets, and balance of payments issues that don't exist in domestic trade." },
      { year: "2020", q: "Balance of Payments is also known as:", options: ["A. Balance of credit", "B. Balance of international payment", "C. Balance of goods and services", "D. Balance of deficit"], answer: "B", exp: "The Balance of Payments (BOP) is formally called the 'balance of international payments.' It records all economic transactions between residents of one country and the rest of the world over a period — covering goods, services, income, and financial flows." },
      { year: "2020", q: "Balance of Payments deficit account may be financed by all EXCEPT:", options: ["A. Selling investments overseas", "B. Decreasing the assets of foreigners", "C. Borrowing from foreign governments", "D. Using the country's foreign reserves"], answer: "B", exp: "A BOP deficit can be financed by: selling overseas assets, borrowing from foreign governments or IMF, drawing down foreign reserves. DECREASING foreign-owned assets (making foreigners sell their Nigerian assets) would WORSEN the deficit, not finance it." },
      { year: "2020", q: "In a comparative advantage scenario where Country A produces 50 rice and 30 beans and Country B produces 70 rice and 20 beans (with 100 units of labour each), Country B should:", options: ["A. Specialise in beans", "B. Specialise in rice", "C. Specialise in both goods", "D. Interchange production"], answer: "B", exp: "Opportunity cost of 1 tonne of rice for B = 20/70 = 0.29 tonnes of beans. For A = 30/50 = 0.6 tonnes of beans. Country B has lower opportunity cost for rice (0.29 < 0.6), so Country B has comparative advantage in rice and should specialise in rice production." },
      { year: "2020", q: "When an economy devalues its currency, the value of its exports becomes:", options: ["A. Smaller in domestic currency", "B. Larger in foreign currency terms", "C. Cheaper for foreign buyers", "D. More expensive for foreign buyers"], answer: "C", exp: "Devaluation makes the domestic currency cheaper relative to foreign currencies. Foreign buyers now need less of their currency to buy domestic exports — making exports cheaper and more competitive internationally. This should boost export volumes and improve the trade balance." },
      { year: "2020", q: "If Nigeria increases tariffs on most foreign goods, then:", options: ["A. Nigerian standard of living would be higher", "B. More foreign goods would be purchased by Nigerians", "C. Prices of domestic goods would increase", "D. Prices of domestic goods would decrease"], answer: "C", exp: "Tariffs raise prices of imports. With less import competition, domestic producers face reduced competitive pressure and may raise their prices. Consumers face higher prices overall — reducing their real purchasing power and standard of living. This is the 'consumer cost' of protectionism." },
       { year: "2019", q: "In a two-by-two model of international trade, it is assumed that:", options: ["A. Both countries gain from trade but volume depends on terms of trade", "B. Both countries gain from trade and the volume does not depend on terms of trade", "C. Both countries gain from trade but terms of trade is inconsequential for distribution", "D. Neither country can ever gain from trade since terms of trade depends on distribution"], answer: "B", exp: "In the basic 2x2 Ricardian model (2 countries, 2 goods), both countries can gain from trade based on comparative advantage, and both can gain simultaneously. The terms of trade determine how the gains are distributed between them." },
      { year: "2019", q: "The quickest way of achieving economic union on a regional basis is to remove all:", options: ["A. Currency barriers", "B. Political barriers", "C. Customs barriers", "D. Language barriers"], answer: "C", exp: "Removing customs barriers (tariffs and trade restrictions) is the most direct and quickest step toward economic integration. It creates a free trade area immediately. Currency union and political union are more complex and time-consuming." },
       { year: "2015", q: "The theory of absolute advantage was propounded by:", options: ["A. David Ricardo", "B. Adam Smith", "C. John Maynard Keynes", "D. Mercantilists"], answer: "B", exp: "Adam Smith developed the theory of absolute advantage in 'The Wealth of Nations' (1776) — each country should specialise in goods it produces most efficiently. David Ricardo later developed comparative advantage." },
      { year: "2015", q: "A decrease in the price of the domestic currency in terms of a foreign currency is referred to as:", options: ["A. Depreciation", "B. Appreciation", "C. Devaluation", "D. Consolidation"], answer: "A", exp: "Depreciation is a fall in the value of a currency under a floating exchange rate system — it now buys fewer units of foreign currency. Devaluation is a deliberate government reduction of a fixed exchange rate." },
      { year: "2015", q: "A rise in the naira per dollar exchange rate from ₦157/$1 to ₦160/$1 means:", options: ["A. The naira has depreciated", "B. The naira has appreciated", "C. The naira has increased in value", "D. The dollar has increased supply"], answer: "A", exp: "More naira are now needed to buy one dollar — meaning the naira is worth LESS relative to the dollar. This is depreciation of the naira (or appreciation of the dollar)." },
      { year: "2015", q: "A floating exchange rate is one that:", options: ["A. Is fixed by the government at a specific level", "B. Is determined freely by market forces of demand and supply", "C. Is periodically adjusted by the central bank", "D. Is pegged to gold or a major currency"], answer: "B", exp: "A floating (flexible) exchange rate is determined entirely by the forces of demand and supply in the foreign exchange market, with no government intervention. It adjusts automatically to correct balance of payments imbalances." },
      { year: "2015", q: "Which of the following nations was the world's leading trading nation in terms of absolute volume of imports and exports (as of 2015)?", options: ["A. Japan", "B. China", "C. Germany", "D. United States"], answer: "D", exp: "The United States has historically been the world's largest trading nation in absolute terms due to its large economy. China has been rising rapidly and has overtaken the US in some years of total trade volume." },
    ],
    west_africa: [
      { year: "2022", q: "The PRIMARY sector of the economy includes:", options: ["A. Manufacturing and construction", "B. Banking, insurance and trade", "C. Agriculture, fishing and mining", "D. Transport and communication"], answer: "C", exp: "Primary sector: extraction of natural resources — agriculture, forestry, fishing, mining. Secondary: manufacturing. Tertiary: services." },
      { year: "2021", q: "Nigeria's economy is best described as:", options: ["A. Heavily industrialised", "B. Largely dependent on oil exports", "C. A purely agricultural economy", "D. A planned economy"], answer: "B", exp: "Nigeria earns the majority of its government revenue and foreign exchange from crude oil exports." },
      { year: "2019", q: "Agriculture accounts for about 60% of the active labour force in West Africa:", options: ["A. Active labour force in West Africa", "B. Arable land in West Africa", "C. Service sector activities in West Africa", "D. Commodity market in West Africa"], answer: "A", exp: "Agriculture is the largest employer in West Africa, accounting for approximately 60% of the active labour force. Despite this, agriculture's contribution to GDP has been declining as oil and services grow — especially in Nigeria." },
      { year: "2019", q: "Which is noted as one of the causes of poverty in West Africa?", options: ["A. Poor manufacturing", "B. Poor leadership", "C. Low crude oil exportation", "D. Low exchange rate fluctuation"], answer: "B", exp: "Poor leadership and governance is widely identified as a root cause of poverty in West Africa — it leads to corruption, misallocation of resources, poor infrastructure, weak institutions, and inability to translate natural resources into development." },
      { year: "2019", q: "The economies of West African countries depend majorly on:", options: ["A. Primary products", "B. Secondary products", "C. Tertiary products", "D. Manufacturing products"], answer: "A", exp: "West African economies are predominantly primary product exporters — Nigeria (crude oil), Ghana (cocoa, gold), Côte d'Ivoire (cocoa), Senegal (groundnuts). This dependence creates vulnerability to commodity price fluctuations." },
       { year: "2015", q: "One major problem facing West African countries is:", options: ["A. Relations with colonial masters", "B. Political integration", "C. Joint military operations in member states", "D. Financial crunch of member states"], answer: "D", exp: "A major challenge facing ECOWAS and West African integration is the financial weakness of member states — many struggle with inadequate budgets, debt, and inability to fund regional projects and institutions." },
      { year: "2015", q: "The highest body in the ECOWAS organogram is:", options: ["A. Authority of Heads of State and Government", "B. Council of Ministers", "C. The Defence Council", "D. The Executive Secretariat"], answer: "A", exp: "The Authority of Heads of State and Government is the supreme institution of ECOWAS. It consists of heads of state/government of all member states and meets at least once a year to provide overall direction and policy." },
    ],
    growth: [
      { year: "2023", q: "The Human Development Index (HDI) measures development using:", options: ["A. GDP per capita alone", "B. Life expectancy, education, and GNI per capita", "C. Inflation rate and unemployment", "D. Population growth and urbanisation"], answer: "B", exp: "HDI combines: (1) Life expectancy, (2) Education (mean + expected years of schooling), (3) GNI per capita. Used by UNDP annually." },
      { year: "2022", q: "Economic DEVELOPMENT differs from economic GROWTH in that development:", options: ["A. Only measures change in GDP", "B. Refers exclusively to industrial output", "C. Encompasses improvement in quality of life and structural change", "D. Requires foreign aid"], answer: "C", exp: "Growth = quantitative (rising real GDP). Development = qualitative (improved living standards, reduced poverty, better healthcare and education)." },
      { year: "2020", q: "Optimum population is attained when:", options: ["A. Population is greater than resources and technology", "B. Population is less than resources and technology", "C. Population matches natural resources and technology", "D. Population greatly exceeds natural resources"], answer: "C", exp: "Optimum population is the population size that, given existing resources and technology, maximises output per person (real GDP per capita). Too few people = underuse of resources (underpopulation). Too many = overpopulation. Optimum = highest productivity per person." },
      { year: "2020", q: "The level of economic development is low in Nigeria because:", options: ["A. Planning has no practical relevance", "B. Of the pattern of consumers' spending", "C. The country is over-populated", "D. Of ineffective plan implementation"], answer: "D", exp: "Nigeria has had numerous development plans (Vision 2010, NEEDS, Vision 20:2020, etc.) but implementation has been chronically poor due to corruption, political instability, poor governance, inadequate funding, and lack of continuity between administrations." },
      { year: "2020", q: "Human capital refers to:", options: ["A. The acquisition of plant and equipment by workers", "B. The amount of financial investment made by individuals", "C. The labour force requirement for sustained economic growth", "D. The education and experience of the working force"], answer: "D", exp: "Human capital is the stock of knowledge, skills, education, training, and experience embodied in the workforce. It is built through education, on-the-job training, and healthcare. Investment in human capital is crucial for productivity growth and economic development." },
      { year: "2020", q: "Which economic growth theory advocated massive investment in several industries simultaneously?", options: ["A. Balanced growth", "B. Dualism", "C. Neoclassical theory", "D. Schumpeterian theory"], answer: "A", exp: "Balanced growth theory (Rosenstein-Rodan's Big Push) argues that developing countries need massive simultaneous investment across multiple industries — because industries create markets for each other. Unbalanced growth (Hirschman) advocates strategic investment in key 'leading' sectors." },
      { year: "2020", q: "Which of the following is NOT a cost of long-run economic growth?", options: ["A. An increase in working hours of the population", "B. An increase in inflation", "C. An increase in environmental degradation", "D. A greater inequality in the distribution of income"], answer: "A", exp: "Standard costs of economic growth include: inflation (demand-pull), environmental degradation (resource depletion, pollution), and inequality (growth often benefits higher income groups more). Increase in working hours is a INPUT/MEANS to growth, not typically classified as a cost of growth itself." },
      { year: "2020", q: "The developmental objectives of an economy with reference to Nigeria include:", options: ["A. Maximising profits for private firms only", "B. Economic growth, employment, poverty reduction, and balanced sectoral development", "C. Increasing military spending as priority", "D. Reducing population at all costs"], answer: "B", exp: "Nigeria's development objectives (as in Vision 20:2020, ERGP, etc.) include: sustained economic growth, employment generation, poverty reduction, diversification from oil dependence, balanced development across regions and sectors, and improved human development indicators." },
      { year: "2020", q: "Common features of developing countries include all EXCEPT:", options: ["A. High dependence on primary product exports", "B. Low per capita income", "C. Advanced and diversified industrial base", "D. High unemployment and underemployment"], answer: "C", exp: "Developing countries are characterised by: dependence on primary products, low per capita income, high unemployment/underemployment, low savings and investment, poor infrastructure, rapid population growth, and low technology. An advanced, diversified industrial base is a feature of DEVELOPED countries." },
       { year: "2019", q: "An indicator of underdevelopment is:", options: ["A. Low per capita income", "B. Low population growth rate", "C. High life expectancy", "D. Low birth rate"], answer: "A", exp: "Low per capita income is the most fundamental indicator of underdevelopment. Other indicators include high infant mortality, low life expectancy, high illiteracy, dependence on primary exports, and rapid population growth." },
      { year: "2019", q: "Which one measures the natural growth rate of a population?", options: ["A. Birth rate divided by death rate", "B. Birth plus net migration equals death", "C. Natural increase equals birth rate plus net migration", "D. Birth rate minus death rate"], answer: "D", exp: "Natural population growth rate = Birth rate - Death rate. If births exceed deaths, population grows naturally. Net migration is added separately to get total population change." },
      { year: "2019", q: "Increasing population in Nigeria affects the economy by:", options: ["A. Automatically increasing GDP per capita", "B. Reducing the burden on infrastructure", "C. Expanding the labour force but also straining resources and services", "D. Eliminating unemployment through labour demand"], answer: "C", exp: "Nigeria's rapid population growth (~2.5% annually) has contradictory effects — it expands the potential labour force and consumer market, but also strains schools, hospitals, infrastructure, housing, and the environment." },
       { year: "2015", q: "Among all the determinants of economic growth, the most important one is:", options: ["A. Land and natural resources", "B. Human capital", "C. Technology", "D. Increased GDP"], answer: "C", exp: "Technology is widely considered the most important long-run driver of economic growth — it allows more output to be produced from the same inputs (total factor productivity). Human capital enables technology adoption and innovation." },
      { year: "2015", q: "One major criticism of foreign aid to developing countries is that it:", options: ["A. Provides incentives for capital flight", "B. Is capital-using rather than capital-saving", "C. Encourages growth in government bureaucracy", "D. Gives too much power to the World Bank"], answer: "C", exp: "A major criticism of foreign aid is that it often strengthens government bureaucracy rather than directly helping citizens — creating dependency, inefficiency, and corruption rather than sustainable development." },
      { year: "2015", q: "Economic development differs from economic growth in that development:", options: ["A. Is measured only by GDP per capita", "B. Focuses only on industrial output", "C. Encompasses improvement in quality of life, reduction of poverty and structural change", "D. Requires foreign aid"], answer: "C", exp: "Economic growth is purely quantitative (rising real GDP). Economic development is broader — it includes improvements in living standards, reduced inequality, better education and healthcare, and structural transformation of the economy." },
      { year: "2015", q: "Which of the following is NOT a characteristic of a less-developed economy?", options: ["A. Low per capita income", "B. High dependence on primary products", "C. Advanced industrial infrastructure", "D. Rapid population growth"], answer: "C", exp: "Less developed economies (LDEs) are characterised by low income, high poverty, dependence on agriculture/primary exports, poor infrastructure, rapid population growth, and low technology. Advanced industrial infrastructure is a feature of developed economies." },
     ],
    macro_meas: [
      { year: "2023", q: "Keynesian economists believe that in a recession, the most effective policy is:", options: ["A. Reducing the money supply", "B. Raising interest rates", "C. Increasing government spending", "D. Cutting the minimum wage"], answer: "C", exp: "Keynesians argue that in recession (deflationary gap), the government should increase spending to boost AD — since private sector demand is insufficient." },
      { year: "2022", q: "Purchasing Power Parity (PPP) is used to:", options: ["A. Calculate a country's trade balance", "B. Compare living standards across countries adjusting for price differences", "C. Measure inflation within a country", "D. Determine exchange rate policy"], answer: "B", exp: "PPP adjusts for the fact that prices differ between countries. PPP comparison gives a fairer picture of real living standards." },
      { year: "2019", q: "An increase in nominal income without an increase in price will result in:", options: ["A. Increased real income", "B. Decreased real income", "C. Increased nominal GDP only", "D. Decreased GNP"], answer: "A", exp: "Real income = Nominal income ÷ Price level. If prices are constant (price level unchanged) but nominal income rises, real income rises proportionately. This means purchasing power has genuinely increased." },
      { year: "2019", q: "Which of the following measures compares income distribution across a population?", options: ["A. Phillips curve", "B. Demand curve", "C. Lorenz curve", "D. Supply curve"], answer: "C", exp: "The Lorenz curve plots the cumulative percentage of income against the cumulative percentage of population. The further it bows from the diagonal line of equality, the more unequal the distribution. The Gini coefficient quantifies this inequality." },
    ],
    labour: [
      { year: "2023", q: "Underemployment refers to:", options: ["A. People who have given up looking for work", "B. Working fewer hours than desired or in jobs below qualification level", "C. People not in the labour force", "D. Seasonal workers"], answer: "B", exp: "Underemployment is a major problem in Nigeria — many graduates work in jobs far below their qualification level, or work part-time when they want full-time work." },
      { year: "2022", q: "Which of the following best describes STRUCTURAL unemployment?", options: ["A. Unemployment caused by a general fall in aggregate demand", "B. Workers moving between jobs", "C. Unemployment due to skills mismatch with available jobs", "D. Unemployment during harvest periods"], answer: "C", exp: "Structural unemployment: mismatch between workers' skills and employer requirements — often due to technology or industry change." },
      { year: "2020", q: "Moses lost his computer engineering job when outsourced abroad, searched unsuccessfully for months, then returned to school. He is best classified as:", options: ["A. Structurally unemployed", "B. Frictionally unemployed", "C. A discouraged worker not in the labour force", "D. Underemployed"], answer: "C", exp: "Moses is a 'discouraged worker' — he gave up actively searching for work. Such individuals are NOT counted in official unemployment statistics because they are no longer in the labour force. This understates true unemployment and is a limitation of official unemployment measures." },
    { year: "2020", q: "The socio-economic effects of increasing population in Nigeria include:", options: ["A. Automatic improvement in per capita income", "B. Reduced pressure on schools and hospitals", "C. Strain on infrastructure, rising unemployment, and potential consumer market growth", "D. Guaranteed economic development"], answer: "C", exp: "Nigeria's rapid population growth (~220 million, growing at ~2.5% pa) creates contradictory effects: it strains schools, hospitals, roads, and housing while potentially expanding the domestic consumer market. Per capita income only rises if GDP grows faster than population." },
    { year: "2020", q: "Increasing population in Nigeria could be curtailed through:", options: ["A. Encouraging early marriage", "B. Reducing female education", "C. Family planning, girls' education, and women's economic empowerment", "D. Banning immigration"], answer: "C", exp: "Evidence shows that girls' education and women's economic empowerment are the most effective ways to reduce birth rates and slow population growth. When women are educated and economically active, they tend to have fewer children and delay marriage. Family planning services complement these approaches." },
    { year: "2019", q: "Labour productivity is best defined as:", options: ["A. The total number of workers employed", "B. The rate of output per worker per unit time", "C. The total wages paid to all workers", "D. The number of hours worked per week"], answer: "A", exp: "Labour productivity = Output / Number of workers (or output per worker-hour). It measures the efficiency of labour input. Higher productivity means more output from the same workforce — key to economic growth and competitiveness." },
      { year: "2019", q: "The effects of HIV/AIDS on the labour force include:", options: ["A. Increasing the size of the working population", "B. Reducing labour productivity and shrinking the working-age population", "C. Having no significant effect on economic output", "D. Increasing labour mobility between sectors"], answer: "B", exp: "HIV/AIDS reduces the labour force by killing working-age people, reduces productivity among those infected (illness, absenteeism), increases healthcare costs for families and governments, and reduces human capital accumulation — all hampering economic growth." },
     ],
    stabilize: [
      { year: "2023", q: "Contractionary monetary policy involves:", options: ["A. Reducing taxes", "B. Increasing government spending", "C. Raising the Monetary Policy Rate (MPR)", "D. Printing more money"], answer: "C", exp: "Raising MPR increases cost of borrowing — reduces money supply, credit, and spending — which brings down inflation. This is contractionary (tight) monetary policy used by the CBN." },
      { year: "2022", q: "Supply-side policies aim to:", options: ["A. Reduce aggregate demand", "B. Increase productive capacity and efficiency of the economy", "C. Raise interest rates", "D. Control the exchange rate"], answer: "B", exp: "Supply-side policies improve the economy's long-run productive potential: education and training, deregulation, tax incentives for investment, privatisation." },
      { year: "2020", q: "The business cycle flows in the sequence:", options: ["A. Prosperity — Recession — Depression — Recovery", "B. Prosperity — Depression — Recession — Recovery", "C. Recession — Depression — Recovery — Prosperity", "D. Recovery — Recession — Depression — Recovery"], answer: "A", exp: "The business cycle follows: Prosperity (peak/boom) → Recession (contraction, falling GDP) → Depression (trough, lowest point) → Recovery (expansion) → back to Prosperity. Understanding this cycle helps governments apply counter-cyclical policies." },
      { year: "2020", q: "Which of the following exhibits a market-based supply-side policy to combat inflation caused by rising wages?", options: ["A. Increasing government spending", "B. Wage controls and labour market deregulation", "C. Raising import tariffs", "D. Expanding money supply"], answer: "B", exp: "Supply-side policies address cost-push inflation by improving productive efficiency: wage controls limit the wage-price spiral, labour market deregulation increases labour supply flexibility. These address the supply side directly, unlike demand-management policies." },
      { year: "2020", q: "The trade-off between balance of payments equilibrium and full employment means:", options: ["A. Both can always be achieved together", "B. Expansionary policies to boost employment may worsen the current account through higher imports", "C. BOP equilibrium automatically creates full employment", "D. Contractionary policy always improves both BOP and employment"], answer: "B", exp: "Policies to achieve full employment (expansionary fiscal/monetary policy) boost incomes and spending, including on imports — potentially worsening the current account deficit. Conversely, policies to correct BOP deficits (contractionary) may increase unemployment. This is a key macroeconomic policy conflict." },
       { year: "2019", q: "Nigeria's 2016 recession was caused by a combination of:", options: ["A. Only falling oil prices", "B. Only security problems in the Niger Delta", "C. Falling oil prices, exchange rate crisis, fuel supply disruptions, power shortages and insecurity", "D. Only inconsistent government policies"], answer: "C", exp: "Nigeria's 2016 recession (-1.5% GDP growth) resulted from multiple simultaneous shocks: oil price collapse, militant attacks reducing oil production, foreign exchange shortages, fuel scarcity, power shortages, and security challenges — the first recession in over 20 years." },
      { year: "2019", q: "When fiscal policy is expansionary but monetary policy is contractionary simultaneously, the result is:", options: ["A. Both policies cancel each other out completely", "B. A policy mix that attempts to balance growth stimulation with inflation control", "C. Guaranteed economic growth", "D. Guaranteed price stability"], answer: "B", exp: "In Nigeria's 2016-2017 response, expansionary fiscal policy (government spending) and contractionary monetary policy (CBN keeping rates high) created a mixed policy stance — trying to stimulate growth while also controlling inflation and stabilising the naira." },
    ],
    intl_inst: [
      { year: "2023", q: "ECOWAS was established primarily to:", options: ["A. Coordinate oil production among West African states", "B. Promote regional economic integration and trade in West Africa", "C. Manage foreign aid to West African countries", "D. Provide military security in West Africa"], answer: "B", exp: "ECOWAS (1975): promotes free trade, movement of people, and economic integration among 15 West African member states including Nigeria, Ghana, Senegal." },
      { year: "2022", q: "The International Monetary Fund (IMF) primarily provides:", options: ["A. Long-term development loans for infrastructure", "B. Short-term balance of payments support and economic policy advice", "C. Military assistance to developing countries", "D. Agricultural development grants"], answer: "B", exp: "The IMF provides short-term financial assistance to countries with balance of payments problems. The World Bank provides longer-term development finance." },
      { year: "2019", q: "The Economic Community of West African States was established on:", options: ["A. May 28, 1977", "B. August 22, 1977", "C. May 28, 1975", "D. August 22, 1975"], answer: "C", exp: "ECOWAS was established on May 28, 1975 through the Treaty of Lagos. It currently has 15 member states and aims to promote economic integration, free trade, and the free movement of people across West Africa." },
      { year: "2020", q: "OPEC is an international organisation known for:", options: ["A. Instigating wars", "B. Creating platforms for economic policies", "C. Coordinating petroleum policies", "D. Financing developmental projects"], answer: "C", exp: "OPEC (Organisation of Petroleum Exporting Countries) coordinates and unifies petroleum policies among member countries to stabilise oil markets. It sets production quotas to influence global oil prices. Nigeria is a member — OPEC decisions directly affect Nigeria's oil revenue." },
    { year: "2020", q: "Which one among the following exhibits a market-based supply side policy?", options: ["A. Nationalisation of private assets", "B. Promotion of monopoly and cartel laws", "C. Embargo on overseas trade and investment", "D. Reducing red tape to cut the cost of doing business"], answer: "D", exp: "Market-based supply side policies improve the economy's productive efficiency through market mechanisms: deregulation, reducing bureaucracy (red tape), privatisation, tax incentives for investment. Nationalisation and trade embargoes are interventionist, not market-based approaches." },
    { year: "2020", q: "If output is valued at ₦7.5 billion and there are 150 million employees, what is labour productivity?", options: ["A. 65", "B. 50", "C. 38", "D. 20"], answer: "B", exp: "Labour productivity = Total Output / Number of Workers = ₦7.5 billion / 150 million workers = ₦50 per worker. This is measured in Naira of output per worker. Higher labour productivity means each worker produces more — essential for economic growth and higher wages." },
    { year: "2019", q: "Which of the following is NOT a member of ECOWAS?", options: ["A. Niger", "B. Nigeria", "C. Ghana", "D. Tunisia"], answer: "D", exp: "Tunisia is a North African country — it is not a member of ECOWAS which is a West African regional body. ECOWAS has 15 members including Nigeria, Ghana, Niger, Senegal, Côte d'Ivoire, Mali, Burkina Faso, and others." },
      { year: "2019", q: "Foreign Direct Investment (FDI) differs from portfolio investment in that FDI:", options: ["A. Is more volatile and short-term", "B. Involves purchase of financial assets like shares and bonds", "C. Involves investment in productive assets like factories and businesses in another country", "D. Is only done by government institutions"], answer: "C", exp: "FDI involves actual productive investment — building factories, buying businesses, establishing operations in a foreign country. Portfolio investment is the purchase of financial assets (shares, bonds) which are more easily reversed and hence more volatile." },
      { year: "2019", q: "Globalization benefits developing countries through all EXCEPT:", options: ["A. Access to foreign capital", "B. Technology transfer", "C. Guaranteed protection of domestic industries", "D. Access to larger export markets"], answer: "C", exp: "Globalization actually REDUCES protection for domestic industries by exposing them to international competition. While it brings capital, technology, and market access, it can harm infant industries that cannot yet compete globally." },
       { year: "2015", q: "One of the potential problems with the European Union is that:", options: ["A. Unregulated free flow of labour may reduce productivity", "B. Economies of large-scale production may increase consumer prices", "C. Tariffs may reduce trade with non-member nations", "D. Government may have difficulty covering shortfall from elimination of duties and taxes"], answer: "D", exp: "When countries join a customs union like the EU, they eliminate internal tariffs. This reduces government revenue from import duties, creating a fiscal shortfall that must be covered by other means." },
      { year: "2015", q: "Currency devaluation differs from currency depreciation in that devaluation:", options: ["A. Occurs under a floating exchange rate system", "B. Is a deliberate reduction of a fixed exchange rate by the government", "C. Is caused by market forces of supply and demand", "D. Always leads to appreciation of the currency later"], answer: "B", exp: "Devaluation is a deliberate government/central bank decision to lower the official fixed exchange rate value of a currency. Depreciation happens automatically under floating rates due to market forces." },
    ],
  };
  
